column85: Cont1 Valve Or Device Fail Ind
column168: Description Of Events

I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A LEAKER AT CITY CLERK SIDE.  WEARING P.P.E., I FOUND A 5-PART HAZ-MAT WITH STAINS ON THE CARDBOARD.  I CONSULTED DECISION TREE & RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID. PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SPILL TUB & REMOVED TO DMP.  INSPECTION SHOWED 12 OF 12 METAL CANS WITH DRY RESIDUE FROM EARLIER LEAKAGE.  ENTIRE CONTENTS WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.

ONE PAIL WAS DISCOVERED PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.  THE PAIL WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: ONE PAIL WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.  THE PAIL WAS RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK.  THE SPILLAGE HAD HARDENED AND WAS DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: ONE BOX DISCOVERED DAMAGED WHEN UNLOADED.  THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH AMPHOMAG AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  THE DAMAGED BOX WAS RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM A LOOSE BUNG.  THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS.

ONE BAG WAS DISCOVERED PUNCTURED AND LEAKING.  THE BAG WAS RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE PAIL WAS DISCOVERED PUNCTURED BY OTHER FREIGHT.  THE PAIL WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE SPILLAGE EVAPORATED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT.  THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH AMPHOMAG AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE PAIL WAS DISCOVERED PUNCTURED BY OTHER FREIGHT.  THE PAIL WAS RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK.  THE SPILLAGE EVAPORATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: BIG CLAMP ON THE BUTTERFLY VALVE IS LEAKING.  DRIVER CHANGED GASKET.  SPILL CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBANTS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: WHEN TRAILER WAS UNLOADED THE MEN DISCOVERED PAILS TURNED OVER IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER BETWEEN 55 GAL DRUM.  THEY INSPECTED AND FORWARD THERE WAS INADEQUATE DUNNAGE TO SUPPORT THE PAILS STACKED AS THEY WERE.  WE WILL SEND COPIER OF THIS REPORT TO ORIGIN TERMINAL TO MAKE THEM AWARE OF THIS CITITUATION.  THIS WILL SHOW THEM  TO CHECK TO SEE PROPER DUNNAGE IS USED TO BLOCK SHIPMENTS

ON STARTING TO UNLOAD TRAILER INTO FACILITY STORAGE TANK, THE CARRIER DELIVERY HOSE GASKET FAILED RELEASING PRODUCT ONTO THE UNLOADING PRO. FACILITY PERSONNEL HANDLED THE CLEAN UP.  HOSE GASKET REPLACED & DELIVERY COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER PROBLEM.
WHILE UNLOADING PALLET THAT APPARENTLY HAD A BROKEN SLAT LIFT DRIVER TILTED BOOM BACK AND BLADE RIPPED BOTTOM OUT OF BOX.

column168: TURNED OFF I-30 WEST TO HWY 67.  WASTE MATERIAL WAS SOLID, BUT TRANSPORTATION SEPARATED LOAD LIKE A CENTRIFUGE, WITH LIQUID TO TOP OF LOAD.  TURNING CAUSED LIQUID TO SLOSH OVER TOP OF END DUMP BETWEEN TRAILER TOP & TARP.  THEN HAPPENED AGAIN AT HWY 229 & VULCAN RD WHERE MAJORITY OF SPILL OCCURRED.  RINECO SAFETY RESPONDED & CLEANED ALL AREAS.  TWO DRUMS (WITH MAJORITY BEING SAWDUST) WERE CONTAINED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DURING SHIPMENT, PALLET WAS BROKEN DOWN AND PAILS WERE STACKED ON TOP OF EACH OTHER-- BUT LACKED PROPER BRACING/BLOCKING.  ENROUTE, ONE PAIL FELL OVER AND A SEEP STARTED OUT OF THE TOP.  IT WAS DISCOVERED AS THE TRAILER WAS BEING BROKEN.

REAR SECTION OF TRAILER WAS DISCOVERED WET AND PELLETS OF ALUMINUM PHOSPHIDE WERE ON THE WET FLOOR.  THE PELLET ON THE LEFT SIDE OF TRAILER HAD DAMAGE TO A BOX AND SOME OF THE PELLETS WERE INSIDE OF THE PLASTIC WRAP AROUND PALLET.  THE PALLETS WERE REMOVED AND THE DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS OVERPACKED. FLOOR DRY WAS APPLIED TO TRAILER FLOOR TO ABSORB WATER. REMAINING LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO FURTHER DAMAGED GOODS WERE FOUND. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

TRANSPORT WAS PARKED AT THE HARVESTLAND COOP AT PITSBURG, OHIO AND HOOKED UP TO THE STORAGE FACILITY TO UNLOAD A LOAD OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA INTO THE BULK STORAGE TANKS AT THE FACILITY.  DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS, THE LIQUID LINE FROM HIS TRUCK TO THE BULK TANK RISER RUPTURED.  A CLOUD OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA COVERED THE AREA IMMEDIATELY AND THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO PULL HIS EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF VALVE BEFORE EXITING THE AREA FOR SAFETY REASONS.  ANHYDROUS AMMONIA RELEASED INTO THE AIR AND VAPORIZED. ADDITIONAL PRODUCT WAS WATERED DOWN BY LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL TO REDUCE THE VAPOR CLOUD.  SOME RESIDENTS WERE VOLUNTARILY EVACUATED.  SOME OF THE WATER/AMMONIA MIX WENT DOWN A STORM SEWER THAT LEAD TO A CREEK. THIS MIX GOT INTO THE LUDLOW CREEK AND KILLED FISH.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUES WERE CORRECTED AND THE OHIO EPA MONITORED THE EFFORTS.  THE DEPARTMENT OF WILDLIFE (DNR) WAS INVOLVED WITH THE FISH KILL.  THE DEPARTMENT OF AGRICULTURE ALSO INVESTIGATED THE INCIDENT.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: EMPLOYEE RANDY GRISHAM HAD NEVER PERFORMED THE PROCEDURE OF OFFLOADING FROM BOBTAIL PROPANE TRUCK TO THE TRANSPORT STORAGE RISER.  EMPLOYEE TURNED BOBTAIL HOSE OFF BUT FAILED TO TURN LIQUID LINE OFF ON TRANSPORT RISER. THERE WAS ENOUGH PRESSURE IN HOSE TO SPRAY PROPANE ON WORKER'S CHEST. THERE WAS A RELEASE OF 3 TO 5 GALLONS.  EMPLOYEE WAS TAKEN VIA CO-WORKER TO BAPTIST MEMORIAL HOSPITAL, THEN TAKEN BY AMBULANCE TO MEMPHIS REGIONAL HOSPITAL @ METHODIST, WAS THERE 1 HOUR AND RELEASED.  BURNS ARE 1ST AND 2ND DEGREE OVER 28% OF BODY IN THE TORSO AREA. PERSONAL PHYSICIAN OF EMPLOYEE GAVE HIM SYLVADENE CREAM AND VICODIN FOR PAIN.  MISSED 1 WEEK OF WORK.

column168: BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED PRODUCT RELEASING FROM TANK CAR WHEN MOVED & CAR ISOLATED IN YARD. RESPONDERS REPLACED BALL VALVE IN KIND (600 PSI, WOG, 1/4 TUM ACTUATING WITH STAINLESS STEEL BALL & DUCTILE STEEL HOUSING) ELIMINATING FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE WHEN CAR MOVED. DRIED SPILLED PRODUCT WIPED OFF TANK CAR SHELL.

BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED ODOR EMANATING FROM TANK CAR & IT WAS ISOLATED IN YARD.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND THAT FRANGIBLE DISC HAD BLOWN & CONSIGNEE RESPONDER REPLACED 165 PSI FRANGIBLE DISC IN KIND.  SPILLED PRODUCT ON TANK SHELL WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH BAKING SODA.  CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION AFTERWARDS.

column168: AS ONE DRUM OF THIS MATERIAL WAS ABOUT TO BE LOADED ONTO A TRAILER FOR SHIPMENT, A FORKLIFT WHICH WAS EQUIPPED WITH A DRUM LIFT ON IT STRUCK THE DRUM CAUSING A SMALL LEAK.  THE CF WORKER PLACED THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE AND MOVED EVERYTHING AWAY FROM IT.  CF DID NOT REQUEST AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE, BUT REQUESTED THAT A CREW COME OUT IN THE MORNING WITH AN OVERPACK DRUM AND SOME ABSORBENTS TO CLEAN UP THE 1/2 GAL OF MATERIAL THAT HAD SPILLED. HOWEVER, THERE IS A GOOD POSSIBILITY THAT THE MATERIAL WILL HAVE EVAPORATED BY MORNING.  A SUBCONTRACTOR WAS SENT TO THE SITE ON THE MORNING OF 6-8-01 AND PLACED THE DRUM INTO AN OVERPACK.  THE LIQUID THAT HAD LEAKED OUT HAD ALREADY EVAPORATED UPON THE ARRIVAL OF THE SUBCONTRACTOR.

BOX WAS FOUND LEAKING & GIVING OFF A STRONG PETROLEUM-BASED ODOR.  THE FREIGHT WAS SEGREGATED FROM THE SORT.  THIS SHIPPER HAS SENT TWO PREVIOUS SHIPMENTS OF UNDECLARED DIESEL FUEL IN THE PAST & THEY WERE REPORTED TO SMELL JUST LIKE THIS ONE.  I NOTIFIED THE FAA CASFO IN SFO.  I LEFT A MESSAGE DETAILING OUR PLIGHT & ASKED THEM TO CALL THE FEDEX STATION IN RANCHO CORDOVA DIRECTLY.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.
THE FREIGHT WAS FOUND LEAKING.  IT WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM & RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AT THEIR REQUEST.

1.  CARGO WAS RECEIVED APPROXIMATELY 1200L ON JUNE 2 WITHOUT ANY IRREGULARITY. 2.  CARGO WAS FORWARDED ONBOARD JL6015/03JUNE JFK/NRT WITHOUT ANY IRREGULARITY. 3.  UPON ARRIVAL AT NARITA, THE CARGO LOADED IN AKE37658JL WAS FOUND CRUSHED AND RETAPED. 4.  JAL/JFK WAS NOTIFIED BY NARITA ON JUNE 4, 2001@ 0232L OF THIS ACCIDENT. 5.  OUR INITIAL INVESTIGATION SHOWED THIS CARGO WAS FORWARED WITHOUT IRREGULARITY FROM TIME OF      ACCEPTANCE TO LOADING ON THE AIRCRAFT. 6.  THROUGHOUT THE DAY OF JUNE 4 WE CONDUCTED A VERY EXTENSIVE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE IF THE IRREGULARITY OCCURRED AT JFK.  AN INTERVIEW WAS CONDUCTED WITH THE AGENT INCHARGE OF MAKING SURE THIS CARGO WAS LOADED IN THE CONTAINER TO BE LOADED ON THE AIRCRAFT.  HE CLEARLY STATED     THERE WAS NO IRREGULARITY.  THE CARGO WAS LOADED WITHOUT INCIDENT. 7.  THE INVESTIGATION CONTINUED ON JUNE 5 AT JFK TO DETERMINE IF ANYONE SAW A D.G. IRREGULARITY ON JUNE 2, 2001.  ANOTHER INTENSIVE INTERVIEW WAS CONDUCTED WITH THE AGENT INCHARGE OF LOADING THIS D.G. THERE WERE MANY PEOPLE PRESENT DURING THIS INTERVIEW.  AGAIN, THE AGENT ADVISED THERE WAS ABSOLUTELY NO IRREGULARITY. 8.  ON JUNE 6, 2001 JAL/JFK CONTACTED RADIAC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES. ALTHOUGH THERE IS NO SIGN OF ANY D.G. IRREGULARITY AT JFK, WE WANT TO MAKE SURE THE WAREHOUSE IS SAFE.  NYC PUBLIC HEALTH WAS ALSO CONTACTED TO MAKE A CHECK OF THE WAREHOUSE.  A VERY DETAIL CHECK OF THE WAREHOUSE WAS MADE WITHOUT ANY SIGN OF ANY RADIOACTIVE CONTAMINATION. 9.  ON THE EVENING OF JUNE 6 ANOTHER INTERVIEW WAS MADE WITH THE AGENT INCHARGE OF LOADING THIS D.G. INTO THE LD3 CONTAINER.  INTERVIEWS WITH OTHER STAFF IN THE WAREHOUSE WERE ALSO CONDUCTED.  ONE OF THE WAREHOUSE STAFF HAD COME FORWARD AND ADVISED OF SOME SUSPICIOUS ACTIVITY HE SAW ON THE EVENING OF JUNE 2, 2001.  WITHOUT INFORMING THE AGENT RESPONSIBLE FOR LOADING THIS D.G. INTO THE LD3, ANOTHER INTERVIEW WAS MADE WITH HIM.  HE AGAIN ADVISED THE D.G. WAS LOADED WITHOUT IRREGULARITY. 10.  ABOUT A HALF HOUR LATER, THE BUILD-UP AGENT CAME INTO MY OFFICE. PLEASE NOTE THIS IS THE EVENING OF JUNE 6, 2001.  HE SEEMED VERY NERVOUS. I BROUGHT OTHER WITNESSES INTO THE OFFICE.  THE AGENT ADMITS HE MISTAKENLY RAN OVER THE D.G. WITH  A FORKLIFT.  HE RETAPED THE PIECE AND LOADED IT INTO THE LD3 CONTAINER.  I ASKED HIM TO GIVE ME A SIGNED STATEMENT HE DID. 11.  ON JUNE 7 ANOTHER SURVEY OF THE WAREHOUSE WAS MADE BY NYC PUBLIC HEALTH.  THE WAREHOUSE WAS FOUND TO BE SAFE.  THE BUILD-UP AGENT IS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE LOADING OF ALL CARGOES ONTO PALLETS AND INTO STRUCTURAL CONTAINERS.  HE MAKES SURE ALL CARGOES ARE PROPERLY COUNTED AND THE PALLET/CONTAINER IS PROPERLY WEIGHED AND TAGGED FOR WEIGHT'N BALANCE PURPOSES.  HE IS RESPONSIBLE FOR MAKING SURE D.G. ARE CORRECTLY LOADED WITHOUT ANY IRREGULARITY. ACTION TAKE TO PREVENT A SIMILAR D.G. INCIDENT A DOUBLE CHECK WILL NOW BE MADE FOR ALL D.G. LOADED ONTO PALLETS OR IN A STRUCTURAL CONTAINER.  THE WAREHOUSE SUPERVISOR MUST BE PRESENT TO SEE ALL D.G. ARE ACCOUNTED FOR

LOADING PRODUCT INTO #2 COMPARTMENT OF TRAILER & IT STARTED DRIPPING THROUGH THE TRAILER BELLY SKIN.  PRODUCT TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER TRAILER FOR DELIVERY FACILITY CONTAINED & DISPOSED OF DRIPPING PRODUCT.  LEAKING TRAILER CLEANED & TAKEN TO A REPAIR FACILITY FOR INSPECTION & REPAIRS

column42: NITRATING ACID MIXTURES, SPENT WITH MORE THAN 50 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: DRIVER ENROUTE TO HIS DESTINATION, HE STOPS @ THE CANFIELD, OHIO TERMINAL OF DART TRUCKING COMPANY, INC.  TO MAKE REPAIRS.  UPON ARRIVAL HE CHECKS HIS LOAD AND NOTICES A SMALL WET SPOT NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE TOTE.  CLEAN HARBORS ENV.  SERVICES RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE TOTE WAS TOO FULL, WHICH CAUSED MATERIAL TO COME OUT THROUGH THE VENT CAP.  APPROX. 50 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS PUT INTO A 55 GALLON POLY DRUM.  FLOOR OF TRAILER WAS CLEANED, ALL CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS THEN PLACED INTO A 20 GALLON DRUM.  THE LOAD WAS THEN ABLE TO BE DELIVERED.
WHILE LOADING, CRUDE OIL CAME OUT OF VENT.  EXACT REASON THE SMALL AMOUNT OF OIL WAS DISCHARGED IS UNKNOWN.  SPILLAGE WAS BIO-REMEDIATED PER THE KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT.

WHILE LOADING, EMPLOYEE OPENED UP DOME LID WHILE CARGO TANK WAS PRESSURIZED. A MIST WAS BLOWN OUT THE DOM LID.  SPILLAGE WAS BIO-REMEDIATED PER THE KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT REQUIREMENTS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: TOTE WAS UNLOADED ON TO A DETERIORATING PALLET.  THE WOOD WAS BADLY WEATHERED.  CRACKED AND UNSTABLE.  THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED ON TO A NEWER MORE STABLE PALLET.  HOWEVER THE TOTE WAS NOT TAKEN OFF THE ORIGINAL PALLET AND DURING TRANSPORT THE ORIGINAL PALLOT FAILED AND COLLAPSED AND A NAIL PUNCTURED THE POLY TOTE.  CAUSING THE LEAK.

CARRIER REPRESENTATIVES RESPONDED AND FOUND THE RELEASE COMING FROM THE PACKING AROUND THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OPERATING HANDLE.  THE CAR HAD BEEN OVERLOADED AND THE PRODUCT WAS BEING FORCED OUT AROUND THE LOOSE PACKING DUE TO HEAT EXPANSION.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED AND THE CAR MOVED TO THE UNLOADING TRACK WHERE IT WAS UNLOADED WITH INCIDENTS.  AFTER UNLOADING THE CAR WAS PROPERLY STENCILLED AND MOVED UNDER FRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY TO A TANK CAR REPAIR FACILITY.

column168: WEARING PROPER PPE, I RESPONDED TO THE UNLOAD WHEN AN IRREG DRIVER DROPPED A FLAMMABLE GAS PACKAGE CAUSING ONE CANISTER TO PUNCTURE ANOTHER. FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS I PROCESSED THE REMAINING CANISTERS AND THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL THROUGH OUR DMP.
DURING UNLOADING AT THE CUSTOMER LOCATION THE FORKLIFT HIT THE CORNER OF TWO BAGS CAUSING SOME MINOR SEEPAGE. THE CUSTOMER ACCEPTED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT.

ENROUTE BETWEEN ORIGIN AND DESTINATION THE VALVE ON THE TANK STARTED TO LEAK INTO THE DRIP PAN. THE DRIP PAN PLUG WAS NOT INSTALLED, DIESEL LEAKED ONTO TRAILER AND ROADWAY. ANOTHER VEHICLE SKIDDED ON THE ROADWAY AND STRUCK GUARD RAIL. NO INJURY REPORTED. HALLIBURTON CONTACTED OIL MOP TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN-UP SPILL.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: UTLX 58390 NOTED DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET BY PRIVATE CITIZEN. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, ENVIRONMENTAL ENTERPRISES, INC., RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP STOPPING THE RELEASE.

GATX 34055 NOTED WITH PRODUCT ON SIDES OF CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL AFTER THE CAR WAS SPOTTED FOR UNLOADING. CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. CARRIER REPRESENTATIVES RESPONDED AND FOUND THE CAR WAS LEAKING AROUND THE PACKING GLAND ON THE TOP OPERATED HANDLE. THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED AND THE PRODUCT WAS BEING FORCED OUT DUE TO HEAT EXPANSION AND A LOOSE PACKING GLAND NUT. THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAD TIGHTENED STOPPING THE RELEASE AND THE CAR WAS UNLOADED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: INTERMODAL CONTAINER RDWZ 269686 WAS NOTED WITH PRODUCT LEAKING FROM UNDERNEATH THE REAR DOORS BY CARRIER PERSONNEL. THE CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, KEISEL COMPANY, RESPONDED AND FOUND THE LOAD INSIDE THE CONTAINER HAD SHIFTED DUE TO IMPROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING. THE LOAD SHIFT RESULTED IN ONE 55 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM  BEING DAMAGED AND RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS REMOVED AND OVERPACKED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. THE REMAINING CONTENTS WERE DECONTAMINATED AND TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER CONTAINER.

INTERMODAL CONTAINER APMU 263323 NOTED DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER BY CARRIER PERSONNEL. THE CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER AND LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE NOTIFIED. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, PETROCHEM INC., RESPONDED AND FOUND THAT 9 STEEL DRUMS WERE "SEEPING" PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OF EACH DRUM WHERE THE DATE STAMP "00" HAD BEEN EMBOSSED INTO THE METAL. APPARENTLY THE STAMPING PROCESS HAD THINNED THE METAL TO THE POINT IT WAS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING INSIDE THE CONTAINER, HOWEVER, THIS DOES NOT APPEAR TO HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THE PACKAGE FAILURE. ONE CARRIER EMPLOYEE WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION AND RELEASED WITHOUT TREATMENT. THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED IN OVERPACK DRUMS AND REPLACED INSIDE THE CONTAINER. ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND COLLECTED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

ENROUTE TO FINAL DESTINATION, LOAD BEING CHECKED IN THE CANFIELD OHIO TERMINAL A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL IS ON THE FLOOR OF TRAILER. CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. UPON ARRIVAL THE CREW LOCATED THE DRUM THAT HAD RELEASED THE MATERIAL. FLOOR OF TRAILER WAS CLEANED AND ALL CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO POLY OVERPACK ALONG WITH THE LEAKING DRUM. LOAD WAS THEN ABLE TO BE DELIVERED TO IT'S DESTINATION.

THE DRIVER FAILED TO CLOSE THE AIR OFF VALVE AF ER LOADING AND LET A SMALL AMOUNT OF ACID TO FLOW INTO THE CROWS NEST THAT RAN DOWN THE DRAIN TUBES ONTO THE HIGHWAY AS A NARROW STRIP .5 INCHES WIDE 1/4 OF A MILE. WHEN HE NOTICED THE LEAK HE CALLED THE GUARD SHACK AND NOTIFIED THE GUARD THAT HE HAD CLOSED THE VALVE AND PROCEEDED TO THE UNLOADING SITE. THE DRIVER WAS SUSPENDED AND THEN TERMINATED.

TANK CAR UTLX80037 WAS ON CSX TRANSPORTATION TRAIN Q63801 WHEN THE CREW SUSPECTED THE CAR TO BE LEAKING. AT CRESTLINE,OH. THE CAR WAS OBSERVED TO BE VENTING FROM THE BOTTOM. CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED. SHIPPER CONTACTED AND RESPONDED TO SITE. SHIPPER FOUND THE 1/4 INCH TEST/ SAMPLE TUBE TO BE BROKEN AWAY FROM ITS FLANGE AND VENTING. AMKO, DOVER, OH RESPONDED AND REPLACED THE FLANGE WITH A QUICK COUPLER, SEALING OFF THE TUBE AT THE FLANGE AREA. NARR: 2 (6) X (2) = 12 X 2 + 24 CODE: 512

column168: DUPX29712,LD ETHYLENE GLYCOL, WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHILE IT WAS SITTING STILL AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN ROCKY MOUNT, NC. THE CAR WAS MOVED TO ISOLATE IT. BY THE TIME IT WAS MOVED THE LEAK HAD STOPPED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. DUPONT SENT A TEAM FROM THEIR FACILITY IN GRAINGERS, NC, ON 06/07. MR. SHERWOOD SHIVER OF DUPONT REPORTED THE BALL VALVE ON THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE HAD BEEN CLOSED PAST THE NORMAL STOP POINT AND WAS NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED. THE VALVE PLUG WAS ALSO LOOSE ALLOWING PRESSURE IN THE CAR TO PUSH PRODUCT UP THE LIQUID PIPE AND OUT THROUGH THE OPEN VALVE. DUPONT ADJUSTED THE VALVE SO THAT IT WAS PROPERLY CLOSED AND TIGHTENED THE VALVE PLUG. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED. NARRI: 5(5+1+0) X (2+0)=60 CAUSE CODE:312

LINER FAILED ON LLCX23202, CAUSING PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM TANK CAR. THE CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WHILE IT WAS IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S GEMTILLY YARD, NEW ORLEANS, LA. CAR WAS MOVED TO ISOLATION TRACK AND TRANSFERRED INTO SOUND CONTAINERS. APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS LOST. NARRI=2(5+5+0X(3+0)=60 CAUSE CODE=653

TANK CAR PROX 13607 REPORTED LEAKING FROM THE FILL AREA OF THE CAR, POSSIBLY OVERLOADED. HAZMAT RESPONDERS FROM COMPANY AND RAILROAD FOUND THE EDUCTION LINE THREADS TO BE FAULTY. TEMPORARY REPAIRS WERE MADE, PRODUCT ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR NEUTRALIZED, AND THE CAR WAS MOVED SHORT DISTANCE TO CONSIGNEE FOR OFF-LOADING. APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE CAR AND GROUND. SPILLED MATERIALS WERE NEUTRALIZED WITH LIME. NARRI=5(5+5+0) X(3+0)=150

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: TANK CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DUE TO FAINT ODOR COMING FROM THE CAR IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S GENTILLY YARD IN NEW ORLEANS, INSPECTION REVEALED LEAKAGE FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) AND THE SLIP-TUBE GAUGING DEVICE. DURING REPAIRS, THE "O" RINGS ON PRD WERE FOUND SMASHED, GREAT DIFFICULTY IN REMOVAL OF RETAINING CAP NUT. THE VALVE ON THE SLIP-TUBE GAUGING DEVICE HAD FAULTY THREADS POSSIBLE DUE TO CROSS-THREADING. THE "O" RINGS WERE REPLACED ON THE PRD. THE THREADS OF THE SLIP-TUBE GAUGE ROD WERE CLEANED, WRAPPED WITH PIPE-JOINT TAPE AND THE VALVE REAPPLIED, WITH NO FURTHER LEAKAGE. CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION. THE ELEVEN UNAFFECTED CANS WERE LEFT IN THE ORIGINAL CARTON AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, TWO CARTONS CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WERE DISCOVERED LEAKING ON THE DOCK.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THREE ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WERE LEAKING.  APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED LEVEL "D" PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP.  THE THREE LEAKING ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS, CARTON AND CARDBOARD THE FREIGHT WAS RESTING ON WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUM.  THE TWO RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS UNDAMAGED INCLUDING THE FIVE, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS IN THE DAMAGED CARTONS.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, AN ODOR WAS DETECTED COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF VAPOR FROM A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM IN A SHIPMENT OF FOUR.  THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF THE DRUM PRESSURIZING WHILE BEING SHIPPED, AND THE CLOSURE OF THE DRUM RELEASING THE PRESSURE.  AN UNDETERMINED AMOUNT A VAPOR RELEASED FROM THE FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED LEVEL "C" PROTECTION AND TIGHTENED THE CLOSURE ON THE FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM. THE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUM AND WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE FOUR FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT TWO JUGS WERE DAMAGED AND TWO WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED, SOME OF WHICH WAS ABSORBED BY THE CARTON AND THE REMAINDER EVAPORATED.  THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF THE CARTON FALLING BETWEEN SKIDS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PLACED THE WET CARTON AND TWO DAMAGED JUGS INTO A CLEAR HAZMAT BAG.  THE BAG WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE TWO UNAFFECTED JUGS WERE REPACKAGED AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

CONTAINER ARRIVED LEAKING & TAKEN TO CONTAINMENT AREA.  CONTRACT RESPONDERS FOUND EIGHT DRUMS ABRADED BY SIDE TO SIDE ROCKING MOVEMENT WITH LEAKS AT THE ROLLING HOOPS.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT EVAPORATED.  TWO ADDITIONAL DRUMS ALSO ABRADED SUFFICIENTLY (WITHOUT LEAKAGE) TO BE PLACED IN OVERPACKS ALONG WITH THE OTHER DAMAGED DRUMS.  ENTIRED LOAD WAS ADJUSTED PRIOR TO RELEASE FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION OVER THE ROAD.

BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED PRODUCT LEAK NEAR MANWAY COVER WHEN CAR MOVED IN YARD.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND FRANGIBLE DISC RUPTURED & SHIPPER CONTACTED TO INITIATE REPAIRS BY REPLACING FRANGIBLE DISC.  BAKING SODA APPLIED TO TANK SHELL TO NEUTRALIZED SPILLED PRODUCT.

BNSF SWITCHMAN REPORTED TANK CAR VENTING IN YARD.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND CAR VENTING AT SAFETY RELIEF VALVE (SRV) WITH SRV RESEATING.  GAUGING DEVICE CHECKED WITH NO PRODUCT OUTAGE FOUND AND CAR WAS ISOLATED IN YARD. EXCESS PRODUCT WAS OFF-LOADED INTO A TANKER TRUCK.  AFTERWARDS, GAUGING DEVICE INDICATED 9 TO 10 INCHES OF OUTAGE WITH NO FURTHER VENTING FROM SRV NOTED.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE DESTINATION ENROUTE BY FLIGHTS FROM ORD - MEM - HNL.  AT THE DESTINATION THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS DELIVERED TO THE HOSPITAL, BUT WAS DISCOVERED EMPTY.  THE CONSIGNEE NOTIFIED CHEMTREC OF THE MISSING CONTENTS, WHO  NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  FEDEX WAS THEN NOTIFIED BY THE SHIPPER OF THE INCIDENT AND BEGAN AN INVESTIGATION.  THE MISSING CONTENTS WERE NEVER LOCATED AT ANY OF OUR LOCATIONS, VEHICLES, OR AIRCRAFT.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOTICED BY THE CREWMEMEBERS ON FLT 3951 ENROUTE FROM IND TO EWR.  THEY REPORTED AN EMERGENCY WITH THE EWR TOWER OF THE STRONG ODOR AND NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO EMERGENCY PERSONNEL AT THE RAMP FACILITY. UPON SAFE ARRIVAL, THE DANGEROUS GOODS THAT WERE HAD BEEN LOADED ON BOARD THE AIRCRAFT WERE CHECKED.  THIS PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE NO PHYSICAL LEAKAGE, BUT A NOTICABLE ODOR. JOE CLARK OF THE EWR/CASFO WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND NOTIFICATION WAS MADE  TO THE SHIPPER.  THE SHIPMENT WAS LATER DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: THIS PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED WHEN SOME HAIR CONDITIONER LEAKED FROM THIS PACKAGE.  WHEN THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST WAS CLEANING UP THIS SPILL, SHE FOUND THAT THERE WERE 6, .4 KG AEROSOL CANS AND 2 HAD LEAKED.  THERE WERE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELINGS ON THE OUTER PACKAGE AND NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS OFFERED TO FEDEX.  AFTER THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP, I WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THIS HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THIS HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT.  THE PACKAGE WILL BE HELD UNTIL THE FAA RELEASES THIS AFTER THEIR INVESTIGATION.

APPROXIMATELY AT 12:00 ON JUNE 4, 2001, A DELIVERY WAS BEING MADE TO A LOCATION.  DRIVER ENTERED INTO A SEVERE STORM WITH A STRONG MICRO-BURST WINDS.  THE PRODUCT WAS LITERALLY PULLED OFF THE TRUCK WHICH THEN FELL ONTO US HIGHWAY 60 WEST.  THE SIKESTON , MO DPS WAS CALLED TO THE AREA WITH A FIRE TRUCK AND TANKER.  WHILE THIS ACTION WAS TAKEN, THE MISSOURI STATE PATROL ALSO CONTACTED THE MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES.  THEY (DNR) CAME AND RECOMMENDED THAT THE FURY BE DILUTED WITH A NEUTRALIZER (TANK CLEANER) AND THEN FURTHER DILUTED WITH WATER FROM THE FIRE TRUCK. BUSTED JUGS  AND CONTAINERS WERE PLACED IN OUR RECOVERY DRUMS.

column168: UPON RAISING THE DOOR OF OUR TRAILER, SAW THAT PAINT HAD LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE PAINT WAS ON THE FLOOR OF THE REAR HALF OF THE 28' TRAILER. column168: A DRIVER WAS AT A SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY PUMPING OUT A WASTE SOLVENT STORAGE TANK INTO A TANKER TRUCK WHICH WAS GOING TO A DISPOSAL FACILITY. THE DRIVER UNDERSTIMATED AMOUNT IN THE STORAGE TANK AND SPILLED FIFTY GALLONS OF SOLVENT ONTO THE CONCRETE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS PUMPED BACK INTO THE STORAGE TANK FOR A FUTURE PICK UP AND THE RESIDUE WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS. THE USED PADS WERE CONTAINERIZED INTO METAL DRUMS. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY THIRTY POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WILL BE TAKEN IN A FUTURE PICK UP TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1200 SYLVAN ROAD IN LINDEN, NJ FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER LOADING AND PUMPING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

A DRIVER HAD RETURNED TO A SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY TO UNLOAD HIS TRUCK. WHEN HE OPENED THE BACK OF THE TRUCK, HE DISCOVERED THAT A HALF A GALLON OF WASTE TETRACHLOROETHYLENE SPILLED OUT OF A 16-GALLON POLY DRUM WHICH HAD A DEFECTIVE GASKET. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE TRUCK AND WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED. THE FAULTY GASKET WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW ONE. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY TEN POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 581 MILLIKEN DRIVE SE IN HEBRON, OH FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION AND CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

DOCKWORKER NOTICED THIS RIPPED BAG WHILE TEMPORARILY STAGED ON THE DOCK. APPARENTLY, SOMEONE HIT THE BAG WHILE STAGING FREIGHT NEXT TO IT ON THE DOCK. NO ONE CLAIMED RESPONSIBILITY FOR THIS DAMAGE SO WE DO NOT KNOW THE EXACT DETAILS. DAMAGED BAG AND SPILLED PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND IS AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION.

WHEN DOKWORKER WENT TO UNLOAD FREIGHT FROM TRAILER HE FOUND TWO FIVE GALLON PAILS THAT HAD SHIFTED FORWARD DURING TRANSIT AND HIT THE FREIGHT IN FRONT OF THEM. SUBSEQUENTLY, AS A RESULT OF THIS MOVEMENT THE TWO PAILS GOT SLIGHT PUNCTURED LEAKING APPROX.2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. THE SPILLED MATERIAL LITERALLY EVAPORATED SO NO CLEANUP WAS NECESSARY. DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO RECOVERY CONTAINERS AND ARE AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION. BETTER BLOCKING, BRACING, AND SECUREMENT COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS MISHAP.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: WHEN LOADING A PALLET OF SAID PAILS ONTO THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER, THIS PARTICULAR SHIPMENT SHIFTED ON THE PALLET AND ONE OF THE PAIL STRUCK A NAIL HEAD THAT WAS STICKING OUT ON THE PALLET.  SUBSUQEUNTLY, WHEN IT STRUCK THE NAIL HEAD IT PUT A SMALL PIN HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE PAIL CAUSING A SMALL RELEASE.  REPAIR PUTTY WAS PUT ON PIN HOLE AND IT WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED WITH ABSORBENT.

column14: HWY 13 ONE MILE S OF MARYLAND
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THIS WAS A SINGLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE (ASLEEP??) AND RAN THE VEHICLE INTO THE MEDIAN STRIP WHERE IT OVERTURNED IN THE DITCH WHICH WAS ABOUT FIVE FEET DEEP.  THE MEDIAN WAS A GENTLY SLOPING GRASS COVERED OPEN SECTION BETWEEN THE NORTH AND SOUTHBOUND LANES OF TRAVEL.  THE GROUND WAS VERY SOFT.  THE STEEL TANK WAS PROTECTED BY SEVERAL INCHES OF INSULATION AND STAINLESS STEEL COVER, WHICH ABSORBED THE IMPACT. NO PRODUCT WAS LOST FROM THE TANK.  THE OVERTURNED VEHICLE WAS ALMOST UPSIDE DOWN.  THE BELLY VALVE WAS REMOVED AND PRODUCT PUMPED FROM WRECKED VEHICLE ONTO ANOTHER VEHICLE FOR TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION.  WITH ASSISTANCE FROM LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENTS, STATE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAMS, COMPANY PERSONNEL MADE THE TRANSFER WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENTS. STATE AND LOCAL POLICE REROUTED TRAFFIC IN BOTH DIRECTIONS ON HIGHWAY 13 FOR APPROXIMATELY NINE HOURS.  THERE WERE NO EQUIPMENT FAILURES.  THE DRIVER HAD BEEN DRIVING AND ON DUTY FOR LESS THAN THREE HOURS AFTER HAVING BEEN OFF 31 CONSECUTIVE HOURS.
PALLETS OF ACID LOADED IMPROPERLY ONTO EACH OTHER.  BOTTOM PALLET HAD THE TOP OF TWO BOTTLES CRUSHED.

A) ACFX 84105, A LOADED TANK CAR OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION, WAS INVOLVED IN A DERAILMENT OF CSXT TRAIN Q36516 NEAR WILMINGTON, OH ON JUNE 17, 2001. THE TANK CAR FELL FROM A TRESTLE AND LANDED ON AN EMBANKMENT TO COWAN CREAK, APPROXIMATELY 50 FEET BELOW. THE IMPACT OF THE FALL CAUSED THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY TO CRACK, AND THE CAR LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 12,300 GALLONS INTO COWAN CREEK. THE CREEK WAS DAMMED BY LOCAL RESPONDERS AND THE PRODUCT WAS NEWUTRALIZED BY CSXT RESPONSE CONTRACTORS. THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT WAS PUMPED FROM THE CAR INTO A VACUUM TANK FOR DISPOSAL. THE CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED AND CLEANED ON SITE PRIOR TO SALVAGE. B) HOKX 111121, A LOADED TANK CAR OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION, WAS INVOLVED IN A DERAILMENT OF CSXT TRAIN Q36516 NEAR WILMINGTON, OH ON JUNE 17, 2001. THE TANK CAR FELL FROM A TRESTLE AND LANDED ON ITS TOP IN COWAN CREEK, APPROXIMATELY 60 FEET BELOW. THE CREEK WAS DAMMED BY LOCAL RESPONDERS AND THE PRODUCT WAS NEWUTRALIZED BY CSXT RESPONSE CONTRACTORS. THE IMPACT OF THE FALL CAUSED THE LIQUID AND VAPOR VALVES, AS WELL AS, THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY TO BREAK OFF THE CAR AND THE CAR LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 16000 GALLONS INTO COWAN CREEK. THE CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED AND CLEANED ON ON SITE PRIOR TO SALVAGE. C) PLMX 33911, A RESIDUE TANK CAR OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT OF Q36516 NEAR WILMINGTON, OH ON JUNE 17, 2001. ON JUNE 2, 2001, KENTUCKY POWDER RELEASED THREE RESIDUE COVERED HOPPERS THAT LAST CONTAINED AMMONIUM NITRATE AND PLACED THEM ON THEIR SIDING FOR CSX TRANSPORTATION TO PICK UP.  ON JUNE 3, CSXT'S TRAIN Q54801 DISCOVERED THESE THREE CARS ON THE MAIN LINE.  TWO OF THE CARS WERE LEANING BUT NOT DERAILED.  THE THIRD CAR, CR 889228, HAD ONE SET OF TRUCKS KNOCKED OUT FROM UNDERNEATH IT AND HAD RIPPED OPENED THE BOTTOM UNLOADING GATE ON THE END POCKET SPILLING SOME RESIDUAL PRODUCT ON THE GROUND.  CSXT DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO CONDUCT THE CLEANUP.  THE CONTRACTOR, HEPACO, RECOVERED THREE 55 GALLON DRUMS (APPROX 1800 LBS) OF PRODUCT FROM THE GROUND.  THE DRUMS WERE TAKEN TO KENTUCKY POWDER AND THEY RECLAIMED THE PRODUCT FOR USE.

"B" END LIQUID VALVE, GATX 422, JUNE 25, 2001, NORTH JERSEY DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 1730 HOURS, MONDAY, JUNE 25, 2001, AT BURLINGTON, NEW JERSEY, WHILE SWITCHING FOR CONSIGNEE COLORITE SPECIALTY RESIN, CONRAIL CREW WPBU29 NOTED VAPORS LEAKING FROM A PIPE NIPPLE ON THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE. FROST BUILD UP NOTED UNDER PIPE OPENING ON TOP OF CAR FROM TANK CAR GATX 422 CONTAINING VINYL CHLORIDE, INHIBITED. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. CUSTOMER IMMEDIATELY INSPECTED AND FOUND THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE PARTIALLY OPEN. THE VALVE WAS CLOSED, SECURING THE LEAK. IN ADDITION TO THE PARTIALLY OPEN VALVE (UNLOADING FITTING NOT DISCONNECTED, NOR VALVE CLOSED PRIOR TO RAILROAD SWITCH),CONRAIL MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, AND LEAD TRAINMASTER, AT THE UNLOADING RACK, NOTED THE SAMPLE VALVE CLOSURE PLUG WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT. SECURED BY CONSIGNEE DURING INSPECTION BY PLANT PERSONNEL. CAUSE CODE 311 NARR=5(5+5+0)X(2+0)=100
CENTRAL'S TANK WAS LEAKING AT THE EXTERNAL VALVE HOUSING. MATERIAL WAS CAUGHT IN BUCKET NOT ON THE GROUND

DRIVER ENROUTE TO HIS DESTINATION, WHEN HE PROCEEDS TO CHECK HIS LOAD HE NOTICES AN ODOR AT THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. AT THAT TIME HE ALSO NOTICES MATERIAL ON THE FLOOR. DART TRUCKING COMPANY, INC. SAFETY DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED. ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED, THEY PROCEEDED TO CALL HEPACO TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE. UPON ARRIVAL HEPACO DETERMINED THAT 4 DRUMS WERE LEAKING DUE TO LOOSE FITTINGS AND THE CHIME NEEDED TO BE TIGHTENED. UPON DOING THIS THE FLOOR WAS CLEANED UP AND THE 4 DRUMS WERE PLACED IN A LARGE DRUM LINER. THE DRIVER WAS THEN ABLE TO PROCEED ONTO HIS DESTINATION.

DURING OFF LOAD OF FREIGHT ON BOARD A SEMI, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO SMALL BOXES IN A SHIPMENT OF SEVERAL PIECES WERE DAMP WITH AN UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE. THE AREA SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED AND UPON CLOSER EXAMINATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE MATERIAL CONTAINED WITHIN HAD LEAKED ENOUGH TO WET THE OUTER PACKAGING. THE MSDS WAS OBTAINED AND REVIEWED FOR PRECAUTIONARY MEASURES TO BE TAKEN. A CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED FOR ASSISTANCE WITH PREPARATION FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

ON JUNE 15 2001 AT 0730 WE ARRIVE TO UNLOAD PRODUCT AT LEHR CORP IN HURON, OHIO.  OPERATOR TOLD US HE MIGHT NOT HAVE ROOM IN TANK TO PUT PRODUCT BUT HE SAID  TO TAKE THE TANK TO 16' 5"  AND STOP UNLOADING. STARTED TO UNLOAD AT O735 AND BOUGHT THE TANK TO 16' 5" AT STOP UNLOADING AT 0815.  OPERATOR SAID TO WAIT TO 1200 SO HE COULD BRING THE TANK DOWN SOME. SO WE WAITED TO 1200.  HE CAME BACK AT 1200 AND SAID TO BRING THE TANK BACK TO 16' 5".  AT 1205 STARTED TO UNLOAD AGAIN. AT 1220 STOP UNLOADING BROUGHT TANK TO 16' 5". HE CAME BACK AT 1325 AND SAID THE TANK WOULD HOLD WHAT WAS LEFT IN OUR TRUCK SO WE STARTED TO UNLOAD AT 1330. AT 1340 STOP UNLOAD TANK WAS AT 17" 6". HE SAID HE WAS GOING TO DO SOME FIGURING TO SEE IF TANK WOULD HOLD PRODUCT. CAME BACK AT 1400 SAID TANK WOULD HOLD THE REST OF THE PRODUCT. 1405 STARTED TO UNLOAD AGAIN. AT 1415 FINISH UNLOAD. WE DRAIN OUR LINE AND SHUT THE VALVE. WHEN THE PRODUCT STARTED TO COME OUT THE VENT PIPE.  THE PRODUCT HAD CAME UP HIGHER THE VENT PIPE AND WOULD NOT LET THE AIR OUT. AIR PRESSURE PUSH THE PRODUCT UP THE VENT PIPE AND OVER THE 90 DEGREE TURN IN THE PIPE CREATING A SUCTION EFFECT AND DRAIN TANK DOWN TO THE BOTTOM OF THE VENT LINE AND LOST SUCTION AND STOP COMING OUT VENT LINE. WHEN PRODUCT STARTED TO COME OUT VENT LINE WE TRY TO CLOSE VENT LINE VALVE BUT IT WAS FROZEN OPEN AND WE COULD NOT SHUT IT .

column168: A DRUM WAS BEING STAGED IN A TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY FOR SHIPMENT.  THE DRUMS WERE DOUBLE STACKED AND ONE OF THE PLY DRUMS ON TOP TIPPED OVER SPILLING ONE PINT OF TETRACHLOROETHYLENE INTO THE CONCRETE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT ON THE WAREHOUSE FLOOR.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH THE LEAKING 16-GALLON DRUM. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 16540 SE 130th AVE, BLDG. 8 IN CLACKAMAS, OR FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM CLOSURE AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: THE DRUM WAS SHIPPED FROM PPG SPRINGDALE ON 6/12/01. THE DRUM WAS LOADED BY PPG USING A FORKLIFT AND A DRUM GRABBER. THE SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT THE 10 DAY IN TRANSIT FACILITY OF ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES L,L,C, ON 6/12/01. THE VEHICLE WAS BEING OFF LOADED ON THE MORNING OF 6/13/01 WHEN THE LEAKING DRUM WAS DETECTED ON THE TRUCK. ROOMS WERE PLACED AROUND THE TRUCK TO PREVENT THE MATERIAL FROM FLOWING DOWNHILL TO A NEARBY STREAM. THE DRUM WAS THEN OVERPACKDED INTO AN 85 1A2. column168: ON JUNE 27,2001 OUR BOBTAIL (PROPANE DELIVERY TRUCK) WAS HEADED EAST ON STATE ROAD 128. A LIGHT RAIN HAD JUST BEGUN TO FALL MAKING THE ROADWAY SLIPPERY WITH (1) THE OIL THAT IS LIFTED FROM THE PAVEMENT AND (2) THE WATER ON THE ROADWAY. IT HAD NOT RAINED HARD ENOUGH TO WASH THIS OIL OF THE ROAD. OUR DRIVER CAME UP ON A CAR STOPPED IN THE ROAD, APPARENTLY TO MAKE A LEFT HAD TURN. IT IS NOT YET KNOWN IF THE BRAKE LIGHTS OR TURN SIGNAL WERE ON OR IF THEY EVEN WORKED. OUR DRIVER APPLIED HIS BRAKES SOME 8 TO 12 CAR LENGTHS BEFORE THE STOPPED CAR. AT THIS POINT OUR TRUCK HYDROPLANED AND BEGAN TO SLIDE INTO THE OPPOSING LANE (INTO THE WEST BOUND LANE.) AT THE SAME TIME A CAR WAS HEADED WEST IN THIS LANE AT WHICH POINT THERE WAS A HEAD-ON COLLISION. THE FORCE OF THE IMPACT KILLED THE DRIVER OF THE WESTBOUND VEHICLE INSTANTLY, AND OVERTURNED OUR BOBTAIL ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE. OUR TRUCK CONTINUED TO SLIDE A SHORT DISTANCE ON ITS RIGHT SIDE. THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ( LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS) PLAYED NO PART IN THIS ACCIDENT/FATALITY. AN INSIGNIFICANT AMOUNT OF PROPANE VAPOR WAS LOST FROM THE PROPANE VAPOR PIPING SYSTEM THIS WAS CAUSED BY A FITTING ON THE VAPOR PIPING SUSTAINING A SMALL CRACK DUE TO THE FORCE OF THE TRUCK ROLLING ONTO ITS SIDE.

column168: BURLINGTON MOTOR CARRIERS HAD PICKED UP A LOAD AT HUNTSMAN CHEMICAL TO BE DELIVERED TO PERMA THERM IN MONTICELLO GEORGIA. DURING THE TRANSLOADING PROCESS, A FORK LIFT DRIVER INADVERTANTLY STRUCK THE CONTAINER WITH THE FORKS OF THE FORK LIFT AND RUPTURED THE CONTAINER APPROXIMATELY 1/2 WAY UP THE SIDE. THE MAJORITY OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRAILER AND WAS PROPERLY PICKED UP AND PLACED IN CONTAINERS TO BE RETURNED TO HUSTSMAN CHEMICAL. A SMALL AMOUNT (ESTIMATED TO BE APPROXIMATELY THREE 5-GALLON BUCKETS) OF MATERIALS DID ESCAPE FROM THE TRAILER. THIS MATERIAL WAS CONFINED TO THE AREA JUST BELOW THE LOADING DOCK. SAFETY KLEEN WAS CONTRACTED TO RESPOND, VACUUM AND PROPERLY DISPOSE OF THE MATERIAL FROM THIS AREA.

DRIVER HAD FINISHED UNLOADING THE PRODUCT AND CLEAR THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE UNLOADING HOSE WITH AIR PRESSURE. column168: ON 7/09/01, FRA INSPECTOR WILL CARTER NOTIFIED THE UNDERSIGNED OF AN UNINTENTIONAL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RELEASE OF AMMONIUM NITRATE FERTILIZER THAT OCCURRED BETWEEN GALLUP & BELEN, NM., BACK IN EARLY JUNE, 2001. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT BN 445338 (COVERED HOPPER) HAD ONE BOTTOM OUTLET GATE AT THE END OF THE RAILCAR PARTIALLY OPEN ENROUTE TO CONSIGNEES UNLOADING LOCATION AFTER DEPARTING GALLUP YARD.  THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED AT 28800 POUNDS OR OVER 40% OF ONE COMPARTMENTS CAPACITY.  THIS PRODUCT SPILLED IN PILES ALONG THE RAILROAD RIGHT OF WAY APPROACHING CONSIGNEES UNLOADING LOCATION.  NO PRODUCT WAS FOUND IN GALLUP YARD.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT CONSISTED OF FINE PARTICLES THAT WERE DISPERSED BY PREVAILING WINDS.  THE MISSING PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED BY WESTERN EXPLOSIVES' SITE MANAGER THE MORNING OF JUNE 4TH, 2001.  THE ATF WAS NOTIFIED BY WESTERN EXPLOSIVES OF PRODUCT LOSS DUE TO POSSIBLE CRIMINAL ACTIVITY.  THE LOCAL BNSF SPECIAL AGENT(RAILROAD POLICE) WAS ALSO NOTIFIED OF POSSIBLE CRIMINAL ACTIVITY.  A JOINT INVESTIGATION BY THE ATF, BNSF POLICE & CONSIGNEE CONCLUDED THAT THERE WAS NO CRIMINAL ACTIVITY ASSOCIATED WITH THIS PRODUCT LOSS; BUT A MECHANICAL MALFUNCTION OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET GATE WITH NO SEAL APPLIED THAT WAS THE CULPRIT.  THE BNSF SPECIAL AGENT INVESTIGATING  POSSIBLE  CRIMINAL ACTIVITY, OVERLOOKED REPORTING THIS UNINTENTIONAL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RELEASE VIA BNSF REPORTING PROTOCOL.

THERE WERE 2 ROOT CAUSES HERE OVER THE DRIVER ENTERED AN INCORRECT QUANTITY FOR THIS COMPARTMENT & TWO THE LOADING RACK HIGH LEVEL SENSOR DID NOT ACTIVATE.  ACTION TAKEN: DRIVER HAS BEEN CONNECTED ON FOLLOWING PROCEDURES-IE-DOUBLE CHECK QUANTITIES LOADING RACK HIGH LEVEL SENSOR HAS BEEN REPAIRED & IS NOW FUNCTIONING CORRECTLY. NOTE- CHEVRON DRIVER WAS LOADING AT THIRD PARTY - EQUILON -EQUILON PERFORMED REPAIRS TO HIGH LEVEL SENSOR.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED FROM LOADING RACK SUMD & RETURNED TO STORAGE TANK. column168: SHORTLY BEFORE 12:00 NOON ON THE 18TH OF JUNE 2001 A CHEMSTATION DELIVERY VEHICLE TRAVELING ON OLD FLOWOOD DR. IN FLOWOOD MISSISSIPPI LOST PART OF ITS LOAD ONTO THE ROADWAY AND NEIGHBORING PROPERTY. THE LOST PORTION OF THE LOAD  WAS MADE UP OF 275 GALLONS (US) OF 50% SODIUM HYDROXIDE. THE CHEMSTATION DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED HIS DISPATCHER OF THE INCIDENT AND THE DISPATCHER SET THE COMPANY INCIDENT RESPONSE PLAN INTO MOTION. CHEMSTATION CONTACTED STATE AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES AND DISPATCHED A COMPANY REPRESENTATIVE TO THE SITE. AFTER CONFERRING WITH MR. BARRY MCMASTERS OF THE MISSISSIPPI DEQ, CHEMSTATION CONTACTED FERGUSON-HARBOUR, INC. AND CONTRACTED THEM TO BEGIN THE PROCESS OF SPILL ELIMINATION AND SITE REMEDIATION. FERGUSON-HARBOUR WAS ON SITE UNTIL APPROXIMATELY 11:00 PM ON THE 18TH OF JUNE AND FROM APPROXIMATELY 7:00 AM UNTIL APPROXIMATELY 1:00 PM ON THE 19TH OF JUNE. DURING THAT TIME PERIOD THEY COORDINATED THE SPILL CLEAN UP INCLUDING THE REMOVAL AND REPLACEMENT OF APPROXIMATELY 30 YARDS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL. ALSO DURING THAT TIME PERIOD APPROXIMATELY 450 FEET OF CONTAMINATED ROADWAY WAS WASHED DOWN AND NEUTRALIZED BY THE FLOWOOD FIRE DEPARTMENT. PH CHECKS OF THE ENTIRE AREA WERE UNDERTAKEN UNTIL EVERYONE INVOLVED (FERGUSON-HARBOUR, FIRE DEPARTMENT, CHEMSTATION AND DEQ) WERE SATISFIED THAT THE SPILL HAD BEEN CLEANED ENTIRELY. AN INVESTIGATION OF THIS INCIDENT HAS DETERMINED THAT IT WAS CAUSED BY THE FAILURE OF A CARGO STRAP USED AS A CARGO TIEDOWN. THE DRIVER WAS NOT CITED. CHEMSTATION HAS ADOPTED A POLICY REQUIRING REDUNDANT STRAPPING OF CARGO IN AN EFFORT TO PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS OF THIS KIND.

DAMAGED CARTON AND LEAKING CARTON REPORTED TO SUPERVISOR BY UNLOADING DOCKMAN. OBNOXIOUS FUMES REPORTED. SUPERVISOR INVESTIGATED AND EVACUATED IMMEDIATE AREA. CALLED CHEMTREC. SUPERVISOR EVACUATED ALL EMPLOYEES FROM BUILDING. SUPERVISOR CALLED FIRE DEPARTMENT. 2 OF 6 ONE LITER BOTTLES BROKEN IN CARTON. DAMAGE RESORT OF EITHER IMPACT TO CARTON OR CARTON BOTTOM BREAKING AND OPENING. CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES HIRED TO CLEAN-UP AND DISPOSE OF RESIDUAL.
NO REMARKS

ON JUNE 16,2001, AT APPROXIMATELY 0330 WHILE DISCHARGING BARGE APEX 3508, THE DOCK OPERATOR DISCOVERED AN OIL SPILL. THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY A FAULTY GASKET CONNECTING THE DOCK HOSE TO THE DOCK MANIFOLD. AT THIS POINT THE BARGES WERE SHUT DOWN AND THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED. A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE OIL WENT INTO THE MISSISSIPPI RIVER, CAUSING A SHEEN. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED AND ALSO I.C.I. ONCE THE COAST GUARD PERSONNEL COMPLETED THEIR INSPECTION, THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND APEX 3508 WAS ALLOWED TO RESTART PUMPING OPERATION. I.C.I. WAS ON SITE FOR APPROXIMATELY 8 HOURS CLEANING UP OIL ON DOCK.

DRIVER SWEPT UP AFTER THE  INK DRIED.

DRIVER HAD ONE PALLET OF 18 PAILS, SHRINK WRAPPED AND BANDED TOGETHER, LOADED ON THE TAIL END OF THE TRAILER. A LOGISTIC STRAP WAS USED TO SECURE THE FREIGHT IN THE TRAILER FOR TRANSIT. PRIOR TO DEPARTING THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, THE DRIVER CHECKED HIS LOAD. THE PAILS ON THE SKID WERE INTACT AND NOT LEAKING. WHEN HE ARRIVED AT HIS FIRST STOP, THE CONSIGNEE, THREE PAILS WHICH WERE LOCATED ON THE BOTTOM ROW OF THE SKID (16 PAILS) HAD FALLEN OFF. ONE OF THE PAILS THAT HAD FALLEN OVER HAD LEAKED ABOUT 2 1/2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. THE CONSIGNEE ASSISTED THE DRIVER IN THE CLEANING OF THE TRAILER FLOOR. IT APPEARS THAT WHILE THE FREIGHT WAS SECURED TOGETHER AND SECURED IN THE TRAILER, THE PALLET WAS ABLE TO WALK OUT FROM UNDER SOME OF THE PAILS, ALLOWING THEM TO FALL.

DURING UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE, ONE DRUM WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM ITS BOTTOM. INSPECTION OF THE DRUM REVEALED A CRACK WAS IN THE CENTER OF THE BOTTOM HEAD. APPROXIMATELY 2-3 GALLONS HAD BEEN LOST. THE SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER AND NEVER LEAKED OUT. THE CONSIGNEE PATCHED THE CRACK WITH DRUM PUTTY OFFERED AND GAVE THE DRIVER SPEEDY DRY TO CLEAN-UP THE SPILLAGE. NO NAILS OR MISCELLANEOUS DEBRIS WAS FOUND TO HAVE CAUSED THE DAMAGE. THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE DRUM AND THE SPILL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL.

DRIVER WAS MAKING DELIVERY TO AN INTERMEDIATE STOP WHEN HE OBSERVED THAT ONE DRUM IN ANOTHER SHIPMENT HAD PRODUCT POOLED ON THE TOP AROUND THE BUNG CAP. APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES HAD ESCAPED BUT WAS CONTAINED TO THE TOP OF THE DRUM. AFTER RECEIVING SAFETY AND PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN A LOOSE BUNG. HE WIPED UP THE SPILLAGE FROM THE DRUM HEAD AND DISPOSED OF THE CLEAN UP PAD AT IN THE CONSIGNEE'S DISPOSAL SYSTEM.
DRUM WAS FORKED WHILE ON THE CARRIER'S DOCK. SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP, THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: TOTE ARRIVED AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY ON THE PICK UP TRAILER WHICH ONE OPENING COVER OFF AND SOME SPILLAGE SLOPPED ON THE TOP OF THE TANK.  DOCK NOTES THAT SOME SECURING PARTS ARE ON THE TOP BUT THERE DOES NOT APPEAR TO BE ENOUGH TO PROPERLY SECURE THE COVER.  THERE IS A HAND PRINTED NOTE AFFIXED TO THE TANK THAT READS, "DO NOT USE - AGITATOR DAMAGED."  DOCK PERSONNEL HELD THE TANK PENDING SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS.  CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER.  THEY WERE ABLE TO DETERMINE THAT LOOSE PARTS SECURE AN AGITATOR TO THE TANK AND ALLOW IT TO ROTATE, WHICH IN TURN, KEEPS THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK PROPERLY MIXED FOR USE.  THE SYSTEM THAT RETAINS THE COVER HAD FAILED, ALLOWING THE AGITATOR'S PADDLE TO FALL INTO THE TANK.  THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE GAVE INSTRUCTIONS ON AN ALTERNATE METHOD OF SECURING THE TANK.  ONCE SECUREMENT WAS COMPLETED THE TANK WAS PUT OUT FOR TRANSIT.

column168: A SINGLE DRUM SHIPMENT WAS SECURED TO THE WALL OF THE CARRIER'S TRAILER, NEAR THE TRAILER'S DOOR. DURING UNLOADING AT AN INTERMEDIATE STOP, A FORK LIFT WAS REMOVING A PALLET OF FREIGHT FROM THE TRAILER. THE PALLET BRUSHED AGAINST THE SINGLE DRUM, PUNCTURING THE DRUM. THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM EMPTIED OUT ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR, AND ONTO THE GROUND. DUE TO THE CONTOUR OF THE DOCK AREA, ALL OF THE SPILLAGE POOLED UP. NO GROUND OR WATERWAYS WERE EXPOSED TO THE MATERIAL. DUE TO THE HOT WEATHER PREVALENT IN THE AREA AT THE TIME, THE SPILLAGE BEGAN TO EVAPORATE RAPIDLY. MANAGEMENT OF THE FACILITY TOOK RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE CLEAN UP OF THE FACILITY AND THE VEHICLE. THE EMPTY CONTAINER WAS RETURNED TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: CARRIER'S SHOP MANAGER OBSERVED A BLUE PAINT-LIKE CONSISTENCY MATERIAL LEAKING FROM A TRAILER THAT HAD BEEN DROPPED AT THE FACILITY'S PARKING LOT. PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING THROUGH THE FLOOR AT ONE SIDE OF THE TRAILER. THERE WERE SPOTS OF MATERIAL ON THE YARD PAVEMENT WHERE THE TRAILER HAD BEEN SITTING (APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON TOTAL). CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN HAD THE LEAKAGE STABILIZED TO ALLOW MOVEMENT OF THE TRAILER 1.5 MILES TO ITS DOCK FACILITY. THE SPILLAGE ON THE GROUND AT THE SHOP FACILITY WAS WIPED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS. DURING UNLOADING AT THE DOCK, A DRUM WAS FOUND WITH A CRACK IN ITS BOTTOM HEAD. ABOUT A GALLON OF ITS CONTENTS HAD BEEN LOST. THE DRUM WAS HELD OFF AND PUT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: ONE DRUM, NOT PROPERLY STAGED ON THE CARRIER'S DOCK, WAS STRUCK BY A PASSING FORK LIFT. DOCK PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY TURNED THE DRUM ONTO ITS SIDE. THEY PUT OIL DRY ONTO THE SPILLAGE, THEN PUT THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. IT WAS SET ASIDE TO AWAIT SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS.

DRIVER REPORTED TO THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN THAT WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY HE ENCOUNTERED A VERY STRONG ODOR IN THE TRAILER.  HE NOTED THAT THERE WAS A FEW OUNCES OF PRODUCT LYING ON THE TOP OF ONE OF THE DRUMS OF MATERIAL FOR HIS THE NEXT STOP.  IT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING FROM A BUNG. THE TECHNICIAN REVIEWED THE PRODUCT CONTAINED IN THE DRUM AND AUTHORIZED THE DRIVER TO CONTINUE TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR ASSISTANCE.  ON ARRIVAL THERE, THE CONSIGNEE'S EMPLOYEE ASSISTED AND CONFIRMED THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR. THEY REFUSED THE SHIPMENT DUE TO THE ODOR.  THEY DID ASSIST BY ATTEMPTING TIGHTEN THE BUNG CAP.  THE CARRIER'S TECHNICIAN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER.  THE SHIPPER CONCURRED THAT THE SERVICES OF CONTRACTOR WERE IN ORDER.  THE CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR WHO WAS ABLE TO AFFECT THE RESECUREMENT OF THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE WAS THEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AT THEIR REQUEST.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: (A,B,C)  CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED BY AN OFFICER OF THE TENNESSEE HIGHWAY PATROL MOTOR CARRIER ENFORCEMENT SECTION THAT ONE OF OUR UNITS HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN A TWO VEHICLE CRASH AND HAD OVERTURNED. HAZMAT PROVIDED THE OFFICER WITH INFORMATION REGARDING THE CHEMICALS ON BOARD AND ASKED IF A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR WAS NEEDED. THE OFFICER DID NOT KNOW BUT SAID HE WOULD HAVE THE SITE INCIDENT COMMANDER CONTACT THE DEPT.  HAZMAT WAS CONTACTED BY THE COUNTY'S EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY SEEKING INFORMATION ABOUT THE INCIDENT. WHEN ASKED IF ASSISTANCE WAS NECESSARY FOR THE RECOVERY THE REPRESENTATIVE DID REQUEST HELP. CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR AND BEGAN NOTIFYING SHIPPERS DIRECTLY AND VIA CHEMTREC. IMPORTANT NOTE: NOT UNTIL APPROXIMATELY 4-1/2 HOURS INTO THE INCIDENT DID THE PERSONNEL ON SCENE ADVICE THE CARRIER THAT ALL OF THE CARGO HAD SMASHED THROUGH THE PASSENGER SIDE WALL OF THE TRAILER. THE CARGO WAS THROWN DOWN A STEEP RAVINE, WITH MANY PACKAGES RELEASING THEIR CONTENTS AS THEY FELL. COUNTY EMA REPRESENTATIVE CALLED AND STATED THAT A LIQUID MATERIAL WAS RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE HILL. HE ASKED IF ANY MORE INFORMATION WAS AVAILABLE ON THE SHIPMENTS. HAZMAT REPLIED THAT IT WAS AWAITING FOLLOW-UP FROM THE SHIPPERS. HAZMAT REQUESTED THAT PERSONNEL ON SITE CONSTRUCT A EARTHEN BERM TO CONTAIN AS MUCH OF THE PRODUCT AS POSSIBLE. CONTRACTOR'S CREW OF 5 ARRIVED ON SITE AT ABOUT 1400. CARRIER DIRECTED ANY EMPTY TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO THE SITE TO TRANSFER SALVAGED FREIGHT FROM THE ACCIDENT UNIT. CONTRACTOR MOBILIZED ADDITIONAL PERSONNEL TO THE SITE, AND A BACKHOE. MOST OF THE PACKAGES THAT WERE VISIBLE APPEARED COMPROMISED. THE SITE CONDITIONS WERE SUCH THAT THE POTENTIAL FOR A LARGE RELEASE EXISTED. CARRIER RETAINED AN INSURANCE ADJUSTER TO PROCEED TO THE SITE. ON ARRIVAL THE ADJUSTER SURVEYED THE SITUATION AND GAVE THE FOLLOWING ASSESSMENT. 1. THE FREIGHT HAD BEEN THROWN FROM THE VEHICLE DUE TO THE CRASH. 2. THE TRAILER WAS LYING ON ITS PASSENGER SIDE . 3. THE CARRIER'S WAS IN GOOD CONDITION AS WELL AS THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER INVOLVED VEHICLE. THE PASSENGER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE HAD BEEN AIRLIFTED TO THE UNIVERSITY OF TENNESSEE MEDICAL CENTER IN KNOXVILLE. 4. I-40 HAD BEEN CLOSED AND A 4-MILE BACK UP WAS CAUSED. THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT MANAGER AND DIRECTOR OF RISK MANAGEMENT HAD A CONFERENCE CALL WITH ITS MANAGING CONTRACTOR TO DISCUSS ITS PLAN OF ACTION: 1. THE DIKE CONSTRUCTED BY THE FIRE DEPT. IS BEING BREACHED BY LEAKING PRODUCT. A CONTRACTOR IS CONSTRUCTING A SECOND DIKE. 2. TENNESSEE EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY IS ONSITE TO MONITOR THE POTENTIAL FOR A RELEASE TO THE PIGEON RIVER APPROXIMATELY 200 FEET FROM THE CRASH SCENE. 3. BEGIN TO OVERPACK LEAKING DRUMS. 4. A ROAD NEEDS TO BE BUILT TO GAIN ACCESS TO THE BOTTOM OF THE HILL TO REMOVE THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND RECOVER THE DRUMS.  5. REMOVAL OF CONTAMINATED DIRT. EPA REGION IV OSC ARRIVED ONSITE WITH REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE US COAST GUARD AND INITIALLY MADE STATEMENTS CR

A SORTER NOTICED A LEAKING PACKAGE.  THE AREA WAS EVACUATED AND A HAZ-MAT RESPONDER WAS NOTIFIED.  I NOTICED A DOT CORROSIVE 8 LABEL ON THE PACKAGE. I DONNED ALL PPE. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR MICHAEL A FRYE AND PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN CECELIA HICKEY RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THE SPILL TEAM PH'D THE SPILL WITH ACID/CAUSTIC TEST INDICATOR PAPER AND FOUND THAT THE CLEAR LIQUID PH'D AROUND 12 INDICATING A MILD TO STRONG CAUSTIC LIQUID.  THE SPILL TEAM DONNED WHAT PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT THEY NEEDED AND OPENED THE LEAKING PACKAGE AND FOUND 3 X 1 PINT EACH GLASS RECEPTACLES OF WHICH 2 WERE BROKEN AND LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART.  THE SPILL TEAM NOTICED THAT THERE WAS ANOTHER PACKAGE GOING TO THE SAME DESTINATION WHICH HAD THE SAME AIR WAYBILL ON A ROUTING LOT LABEL, BUT THE CONSIGNEE'S NAME AND ADDRESS WAS NOT MARKED ON THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE THAT CONTAINED THE 2 BROKEN GLASS RECEPTACLES LEAKED SO BADLY THAT THE CONSIGNEE'S NAME AND ADDRESS WAS COMPLETELY OBLITERATED.  ALSO DISCOVERED IN THE PACKAGE WAS A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WHICH DESCRIBED THE PRODUCT AND THAT IT WAS IN FACT CORROSIVE ALTHOUGH INDICATED THAT IT WAS A MILD CORROSIVE.  THE 2 PIECE SHIPMENT WERE AIRBORNE EXPRESS BOXES AND NOT DESIGNED FOR SHIPPING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE TWO BOXES WERE DOUBLED BAGGED AND FURTHER PLACED INTO A DOT 1A1 STEEL SPECIFICATION DRUM AND TAKEN TO OUR HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY AND PLACED UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN A SECURITY CAGE TO BE HELD UNTIL THE FAA COULD INVESTIGATE THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE IN FACT A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. NO ONE WAS IN CONTACT. CLEAR OF SCENE: 10:50 A.M.

FILE:3073 D, SHIPPER: ACROS ORGANICS, AWB# EDS 79164737745 MBS. ON 06/15/2001, A CALL CAME IN TO OUR HAZ MAT DISPATCH OFF ICE THAT THERE WAS A STEEL DRUM EMITTING  AN ODOR OF ACETONE AND APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED AT THE TOP, THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION WAS AT DOOR H-2 OF OUR HAZ MAT SORT BUILDING 207.  THE PERSON IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR ONLY WAS PART SPILL TECHNICIAN JEFFERY KIDDER. HAZ MAT COORDINATOR CHUCK JONES WAS IN CHARGE OF THIS AREA AND CALLED FOR PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS JEFFERY KIDDER  AND DIANE RAMSDEN TO DONN THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND TO APPROACH THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION TO INVESTIGATE CLOSER.  UPON ARRIVAL THE SPILL TECHNICIANS DOUBLE BAGGED THE STEEL DRUM AND PLACED IT INTO A DOT SPECIFICATION UN 1A1 SALVAGE DRUM FOR FORWARDING TO IT'S FINAL DESTINATION. PART TIME JEFFERY KIDDER WHO WAS IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR REQUIRED NO MEDICAL ATTENTION AND DID NOT MISS ANY WORK TIME. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND WAS ACCOMPANIED BY A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS. CLEAR OF SCENE: 00:00 A.M.

column168: FILE: 3074 D, SHIPPER: INKWARE, INC., AWB# LAS 4811468185 ON 06/15/2001, A CALL CAME INTO OUR HAZ MAT DISPATCH ADVISING THAT THERE WAS A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN LOWER BELLY COMPARTMENT 2, OF ONE OF OUR AIRCRAFT, N 820 AX ON "D" RAMP AT GATE D-22 OF OUR SORT HUB FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177.  ABX HAZ MAT DISPATCH CALLED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR CHARLES JONES, PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, JEFFERY KIDDER AND DIANE RAMSDEN TO RESPOND.  THE SPILL TEAM ARRIVED PLANESIDE AT 02:56 A.M.  AS THEY WERE ALREADY IN VICINITY OF THE AIRCRAFT AND THEY DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND BEGAN TO SEARCH THROUGH THE CARGO.  UPON FINDING THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION THEY REMOVED IT FROM THE CARGO COMPARTMENT AND CLEANED A SMALL AMOUNT FROM THE FLOOR OF THE CARGO COMPARTMENT.  THE SPILL TEAM OPENED THE PACKAGE TO DETERMINE WHAT WAS LEAKING AND UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE THEY FOUND 4 X 1 GALLON EACH PLASTIC JUGS, 1 OF WHICH HAD A SMALL PUNCTURE IN THE SIDE OF IT.  IT IS UNKNOWN WHAT CAUSED THE PUNCTURE.  THE SPILL TEAM, CLOSED UP THE FIBERBOARD BOX AND PLACED IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH AN ABSORBENT PAD AND FURTHER PLACED IT IN A DOT 1A1 STEEL SALVAGE DRUM SO THE SHIPMENT COULD CONTINUE IN TRANSIT TO ITS FINAL DESTINATION.  THERE WERE TWO PACKAGES OF SAME TYPE IN THIS SHIPMENT AND THEY WERE BOTH PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PACKAGED FOR TRANSPORT BY AIR AND THE SHIPMENT WAS ACCOMPANIED BY A SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS.  THE EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT GOT A SMALL AMOUNT ON HIS HANDS AND PER PROCEDURES WENT WAND WASHED HIS HANDS WITH MILD SOAP AND WARM WATER. THERE ARE DIGITAL PHOTOS ON FILE FOR THIS SHIPMENT.

ONCE THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THERE WAS LIQUID COMING OUT OF THE REAR OF HIS TRAILER HE CONTACTED HIS REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER, WHICH IN TURN CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT INC.  E M I SENT A SUBCONTRACTOR TO THE SITE WHICH FOUND A LEAKING 55 GAL DRUM OF AND ACETONE SOLUTION.  THE SUBCONTRACTORS NOTED THAT IT APPEARED THAT THE DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A LOAD SHIFT OF OTHER FREIGHT INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND LEFT ON THE TRAILER WHILE THE SPILLED MATERIALS WERE CLEANED UP AND TAKEN FOR DISPOSAL. EMI JOB#11000

WHILE LOADING A PASSENGER BAG BELONGING TO PHUONG NGUYEN, OUR EMPLOYEES NOTICED A  STRONG ACETONE LIKE ODOR, WHICH MADE THEM DIZZY. THEY GOT OUT OF THE  BELLY AND CALLED FOR AN ENVIRONMENTAL COORDINATOR. THE EMPLOYEES WERE SENT TO AA MEDICAL AND EXAMINED AND LATER RELEASED. THE PASSENGER ADVISED THE SMELL TO BE FROM A PRODUCT USED TO PUT TOPSPIN ON PING-PONG BALLS TO ENHANCE PERFORMANCE DURING TOURNAMENTS. HE OPENED THE BAG AND SHOWED US THE PRODUCT "SUPER CHACK" WHICH WAS INSIDE 3 PLASTIC ZIP LOCK SANDWICH BAGS. LESS THAN AN OUNCE OF FLUID HAD LEAKED INTO THE INNERMOST SANDWICH BAG, THE ITEM WAS REMOVED FROM THE LUGGAGE AND TAKEN TO A DG STORAGE AREA FOR DISPOSAL. COPIES OF THE DRIVER'S LICENSE, ADDRESS, AND PHONE NUMBER WERE OBTAINED FROM THE PASSENGER FOR THE FAA. THE PASSENGER WAS ADVISED CARRYING UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS ON BOARD AN AIRCRAFT IS PROHIBITED.

column168: FILE:  2138 F & 2138 D, SHIPPER:  TCM MFG, USA AWB #KGJ 7341905955 YHM.  ON 06/16/2001 AT 0015 A SPILL WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 207 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILIMINGTON, OHIO 45177. PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS EUGENE LOVAS AND RANDY WILLIAMS DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX WITH OBVIOUS SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGING. THEY REMOVED THIS FROM THE SORT BELT, WHICH WAS DOWN DUE TO SPILL, AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THIS BOX TO CONTAIN 2X1 GALLON METAL CANS WITH METAL FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES, WITH NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE, RESULTING IN THE LEAKAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 2 QUARTS FROM ONE OF THE CANS.  THESE CANS WERE LOADED ON THEIR SIDES IN THIS BOX, WHICH DID NOT CONTAIN ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS FOUND THAT THESE CANS HAD "FLAMMABLE" ON THE BACK LABEL ON EACH CAN. THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS INTO THE BOX, RESEALED IT AND PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS PLACED INTO THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE AREA INVOLVED WAS CLEANED WITH SOAP AND WATER, AND WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  THERE WERE 3 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR. THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK OPERATIONS.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES WERE REPORTED WITH THESE EMPLOYEES.  NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATED THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  A COPY OF THE INVOICE WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0049.

FILE:  3079 D, SHIPPER:  LINDA RIOUX, AWB # YUL 4009592058 IEL.  ON 06/14/2001 AT 0203 A SPILL WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 207 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS LORINE HARNER AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR CHARLES JONES DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BLACK METAL DRUM WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE AROUND THE BUNG CLOSURE.  THEY REMOVED THIS FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN A CLOSER INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THAT THIS DRUM HAD A LABEL ON THE BACKSIDE STATING " NON REGULATED" AND ON THE FRONT LABEL IT STATES "BB-332 LIQUID PHENOL FORMALDEHYDE RESIN" AND "ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID N.O.S. (FORMALDEHYDE PHENOL), UN 3082.  THEY TIGHTENED THE BUNG CLOSURE AND PLACED THIS DRUM INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THIS DRUM IS CURRENTLY ON HOLD AT ILN.  AWAITING A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE PRODUCT.  SHE WASHED HER HANDS, WAS ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.  NO CHANGES REPORTED IN THIS EMPLOYEE.  NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE AT ILN.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0212.

FILE:  3078 D, SHIPPER:  SIGMA-ALDRICH, INC., AWB# MKE 46049352784 NJS.  ON 06/11/2001 AT 2324 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 208 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS JEFFREY KIDDER AND JOSHUA TIRADO DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS SUSPECTED TO BE EMITTING AN ODOR.  THEY REMOVED THIS FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN A PLASTIC BAG WITH 10 SMALLER FIBERBOARD BOXES INSIDE OF IT.  NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THESE BOXES WERE ALL SATURATED.  EACH SMALL BOX CONTAINED A IL GLASS BOTTLE WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, ONE OF THESE BOTTLES WAS FOUND TO BE BROKEN FROM THE MIDDLE TO THE BOTTOM.  CAUSING IT TO LEAK ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS.  LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN THE PLASTIC BAG.  ALL ITEMS WERE REPLACED INTO THE PLASTIC BAG AND BOX.  RESEALED AND PLACED INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED IT TO ALDRICH CHEMICAL COMPANY.  THE BOX WAS PROPERLY MARKED.  LABELED AND HAD THE APPROPRIATE HAZ CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING IT.  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  THERE WERE 2 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREA NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.  NO CHANGES WERE REPORTED IN THESE EMPLOYEES.  NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE AT ILN.  CLEAR OF SCENE 2339.

column168: SKID WAS NOT LEAKING ON ORIGINAL TRAILER.  DSR GREEN LOADED SKID ONTO WRONG TRAILER THINKING IT WAS PART OF ANOTHER ORDER,  HE THEN UNLOADED SKID OFF TRAILER AND SAW A LEAK ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  HE PUT CARDBOARD DOWN AND CHECK OUT THE SKID TO DETERMINE WHERE IT WAS LEAKING, HE THEN REALIZED IT WAS 6.1 TOXIC, AND CALL MYSELF TO CHECK SKID OUT.  I INSTRUCTED DSR GREEN TO LOAD IN ORIGINAL TRAILER  AND CLOSE DOOR.  I ALSO INSTRUCTED GREEN TO CLOSE THE OTHER TRAILER DOOR.  I CALLED CHEMTREC TO CHECK MATERIAL OUT AND DETERMINE IF WE COULD CLEAN TRAILER THAT SPILL OCCURRED.  MSDS INDICATED WE SHOULD CALL IN CLEAN-UP CREW.  PULLED BOTH TRAILERS IN YARD FOR CLEAN-UP CREW.  NEED TO CHECK THE SKID AND PAIL OUT TO DETERMINE IF THE INCIDENT WAS CAUSE BY IMPROPER LOADING AND FORKLIFT DAMAGE.  PAILS DID NOT LOOK LIKE IT WAS LOADED ON TOP OF CARDBOARD ON TOP OF THE SKID TO PREVENT DAMAGE FROM NAILS IN SKID.  CAP ON 1 5GAL PAIL CAME LOOSE AND ALLOWED THE SPILLAGE.

VAPOR LEAK AT GAGE ROD PACKING ON-A FOUND VERY SMALL VAPOR LEAK GAGE ROD ON-B BOTH CAR REPAIRED BY EAGLE CONSTRUCTOR AND HULCHER. AT APPROXIMATELY 4:45 AM ON SATURDAY, JUNE 16, 2001, I RECEIVED A CALL  AT MY HOME REPORTING A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM A TANK CAR LOCATED IN FRANCE YARD. UPON MY ARRIVAL I FOUND AN ODOR COMING FROM A CPDX 180093. I IMPLEMENTED OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE PLAN. NEW ORLEANS FIRE DEPARTMENT CAPTAIN W. PARKER AND MYSELF MOUNTED THE CAR AND FOUND A VAPOR LEAK A GAGE ROD PACKING GLAND. I NOTIFIED EAGLE CONSTRUCTION TO RESPOND. AFTER SPEAKING WITH LA.STATE POLICE MAJOR RONNIE MAYEAU, HE DECIDE TO HAVE CHEVRON INSPECT ALL TANK CARS WITHIN THE SAME NUMBER SERIES DUE TO PROBLEMS THAT HAVE OCCURRED OVER THE LAST FEW DAYS WITH THESE CARS. HE CONTACTED CHEVRON WHO THEN CONTRACTED TO HULCHER THE TASK OF INSPECTING THE CARS. HULCHER RESPONDED TO FRANCE YARD ALONG WITH EAGLE AND WERE ABLE TO STOP THE LEAK ON THE CPDX180093. THEY INSPECTED ANOTHER CAR, CDPX180046 WHICH WAS IN THE SAME TRAIN AND FOUND A SLIGHT LEAK FROM THE SAME LOCATION. THIS WAS ALSO REPAIRED.J MORROW AND J BERTUCCI ALSO RESPONDED AS MEMBERS OF THE BLUE GOAX TEAM. NO INJURIES OR OTHER MEDICAL NEEDS WERE REPORTED BY ANY NOPB EMPLOYEE.

column168: ON JUNE 15 2001 AT 0730 WE ARRIVED TO UNLOAD PRODUCT AT LEAR CORP IN HURON OHIO.  OPERATOR TOLD US HE MIGHT NOT HAVE ROOM IN TANK TO PUT PRODUCT BUT HE SAID TO TAKE THE TANK TO 16' 5" AND STOP UNLOADING STARTED TO UNLOAD AT 0735 AND BOUGHT THE TANK TO 16' 5" AT STOP UNLOADING AT 0815.  OPERATOR SAID TO WAIT TO 1200 SO HE COULD BRING THE TANK DOWN SOME.  SO WE WAITED TO 1200.  HE CAME BACK AT 1200 AND SAID TO BRING THE TANK BACK TO 16' 5" AT 1205 STARTED TO UNLOAD AGAIN AT 1220 STOP UNLOADING BROUGHT TANK TO 16' 5". HE CAME BACK AT 1325 AND SAID THE TANK WOULD HOLD WHAT WAS LEFT IN OUR TRUCK.  SO WE STARTED TO UNLOAD AT 1330 AT 1340 STOP UNLOAD TANK WAS AT 17' 6" HE SAID HE WAS GOING TO DO SOME FIGURING TO SEE IF TANK WOULD HOLD PRODUCT.  CAME BACK AT 1400 SAID TANK WOULD HOLD THE REST OF THE PRODUCT 1405 STARTED TO UNLOAD AGAIN.  AT 1415 FINISH UNLOAD.  WE DRAIN OUR LINE AND SHUT THE VALVE.  WHEN THE PRODUCT STARTED TO COME OUT THE VENT PIPE. THE PRODUCT HAD CAME UP HIGHER THE VENT PIPE AND WOULD NOT LET THE AIR OUT AIR PRESSURE PUSH THE PRODUCT UP THE VENT PIPE AND OVER THE 90 TURN IN THE PIPE CREATING A SUCTION EFFECT.  AND DRAIN TANK DOWN TO THE BOTTOM OF THE VENT LINE AND LOST SUCTION AND STOP COMING OUT VENT LINE WHEN PRODUCT STARTED TO COME OUT VENT LINE WE TRY TO CLOSE VENT LINE VALVE BUT IT WAS FROZEN OPEN AND WE COULD NOT SHUT IT.  JAMES WHOT SR

column168: AIRCRAFT N207ME ARRIVED FROM MCI APPROXIMATELY 1145 CDT AND PARKED AT GATE 34 IN MKE. THE RAMP AGENTS OPEN THE AFT CARGO BIN DOORS AND ENCOUNTERED A STRONG SMELL OF GASOLINE. MAINTENANCE WAS CONTACTED AND THE BIN WAS CAREFULLY UNLOADED TO FIND A CARDBOARD BOX SATURATED ON ONE SIDE WITH GASOLINE.  GASOLINE WAS FOUND ON THE FLOOR OF THE CARGO BIN. THE BOX WAS A BEING SHIPPED AS PRIORITY MAIL THROUGH THE U.S. POSTAL SERVICE AND WAS ADDRESSED: FROM: JASON BROWN 10470 ST. RT. 17 WEST PLAINS, MO 65775 TO: RICK JACOBSON 4281 N. GALAXY DR. JANESVILLE, WI THE BOX WAS A USED BOX WITH MARKINGS FROM KOHLER PLUMBING ON THE OUTSIDE, TAPED UP WITH POSTAL  TAPE AND ADDRESSED WITH GENERAL USE LABELS.  NO MARKINGS ON THE BOX INDICATED THAT THE CONTENTS WERE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, OR SOMETHING OTHER THAN PLUMBING ITEMS. THE SENDER OF THE BOX INDICATED THAT IT CONTAINED A CHAINSAW AND THAT THE GASOLINE HAD NOT ALL BEEN DRAINED. THE BOX WAS RECEIVED OVER THE COUNTER BY AN ACCEPTING CLERK AT THE KANSAS CITY POST OFFICE WHO APPARENTLY HAD NOT ASKED SPECIFIC QUESTIONS CONCERNING THE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE. REGULAR PROCEDURES FOR A POSTAL FACILITY INCLUDE THE SCREENING OF QUESTIONABLE PACKAGE, HOWEVER, SINCE THIS PACKAGE HAD NO HAZMAT LABEL, THIS WAS APPARENTLY NOT DONE. THE PACKAGE WAS FORWARDED TO A STAGING AREA AT THE KANSAS CITY AIRPORT WHERE AGENTS FROM MIDWEST EXPRESS PICK UP MAIL DESIGNATED FOR OUR FLIGHTS AND SEPARATE THE MAIL BY DESTINATION.  THE MAIL IS PLACED ON CARTS AND TAKEN TO THE AIRCRAFT. AGENTS WORKING FLIGHT 3, AIRCRAFT N207ME, DID NOT NOTICE ANYTHING UNUSUAL ABOUT THE PACKAGE, NOR DID THEY NOTICE ANY UNUSUAL SMELL DURING THE TRANSFER AND LOADING PROCESS. THE LEAKING COULD HAVE OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THE BOX BEING LOADED UPSIDE DOWN, OR A RESULT OF THE CHANGE IN PRESSURE. A POSTAL AGENT RETRIEVED THE BOX AND NOTIFIED POSTAL OFFICIALS OF THE INCIDENT FOR FOLLOW-UP. AIRCRAFT N270ME WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE FOR CLEAN UP OF APPROX. 1-2 PINTS OF GASOLINE.  FLOORBOARDS WERE REMOVED TO ENSURE THAT THE GASOLINE HAD NOT GOTTEN INTO THE INSULATION.  NO RESIDUAL FUEL WAS FOUND.  FLOOR TAPE HAD BEEN SATURATED AND WAS REPLACED. WORK ORDER 30733 WAS USED TO TRACK THE MATERIALS AND LABOR FOR THE CLEANUP. THE WORK ORDER SHOWS A TOTAL OF 10.5 MAN-HOURS = $179.77

NORTH AMERICAN AIRCRAFT SERVICE (NAAS), A FUEL COMPANY OUT OF SAN ANTONIO, TEXAS, WAS CONTRACTED BY MIDWEST EXPRESS TO PROVIDE AIRCRAFT FUEL TANK REPAIR SERVICES FOR AIRCRAFT IN THE MAINTENANCE HANGER IN MILWAUKEE. NAAS MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR MR. BROOKS TO FLY TO MKE ALONG WITH THE EQUIPMENT REQUIRED TO COMPLETE THE FUEL TANK REPAIRS. NORMALLY, NAAS HAS A SHOP PERSON PREPARE THE ROAD KIT FOR TRANSPORTING EQUIPMENT; IN THIS CASE, THE SHOP PERSON WAS ON VACATION AND MR, BROOKS PREPARED THE EQUIPMENT HIMSELF FOR TRANSPORTATION FROM SAT TO MKE ON FLIGHT 589, FRIDAY, JUNE 23RD. WHEN THE AIRCRAFT ARRIVED IN MCI, THE RAMP AGENTS OPENED THE CARGO BIN AND ENCOUNTERED A STRONG FUEL SMELL.  THEY IDENTIFIED THE SOURCE AS ONE OF THE CASES BEING TRANSPORTED BY MR. BROOKS CONTAINING A SUMP BARREL FOR AIRCRAFT FUEL. THE AGENTS REMOVED THE CASE FROM THE AIRCRAFT REFUSING ITS CONTINUED TRANSPORT ON THE AIRCRAFT.  MAINTENANCE TECHNICIANS OPENED THE CASE TO CHECK FOR THE PRESENCE OF FUEL.  ALTHOUGH THE CASE SMELLED OF FUEL, THEY FOUND IT CLEAN AND DRY WITH NO INDICATION OF RESIDUAL  FUEL.  THEY PREPARED IT FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORT TO MKE  THE FOLLOWING DAY. UPON COMPLETION OF HIS WORK IN MKE, MR. BROOKS AGAIN CLEANED AND PREPARED THE EQUIPMENT FOR ITS RETURN TO SAT.  THE CASES AND TOOLBOX WERE LOADED ON AIRCRAFT N300ME FOR FLIGHT 580, WEDNESDAY, JUNE 27TH. WHEN THE AIRCRAFT ARRIVED AT ITS STOP IN MCI, RAMP AGENTS OPENED THE AIRCRAFT CARGO BIN DOOR TO UNLOAD THE BAGGAGE.  UPON ENCOUNTERING A VERY STRONG SMELL OF FUEL, THE AGENTS AGAIN SEARCHED FOR THE IDENTIFIED THE SOURCE OF THE SMELL AS ONE OF THE CASES BEING TRANSPORTED BY MR. BROOKS. MR. BROOKS STATED THAT HE CLEANED THE FILTER THAT WAS USED IN THE FUEL VACUUM DURING HIS WORK AT THE MAINTENANCE HANGAR, HOWEVER FUEL REMAINED AND LEAKED OUT OF THE FILTER AND OUT OF THE CASE RESULTING IN A SPILL APPROXIMATELY 4" WIDE AND 5' LONG. THE RAMP AGENTS REMOVED THE CASES AND TOOLBOX FROM THE AIRCRAFT, AND DID NOT ALLOW THEM TO CONTINUE ON THE FLIGHT. BECAUSE THE FUEL WAS CONTAINED ON THE METAL STRIP DOWN THE CENTER OF THE BAG PIT FLOOR, THE MAINTENANCE TECHNICIANS WERE ABLE TO COMPLETE A QUICK CLEAN UP AND FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE AIRCRAFT WAS NOT REQUIRED. THE BAGGAGE SERVICES DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED THAT NAAS ACCEPTS RESPONSIBILITIES FOR ANY BAG CLAIMS BY PASSENGER AS A RESULT OF THE FUEL SPILL.

REGIONAL MGR CTS,TIM OBRIEN RECEIVED A REPORT FROM CHANNELVIEW FIRE DEPARTMENT THAT AN ODOR HAD BEEN DETECTED IN A NEIGHBORHOOD NEAR FAUNA SIDING IN HOUSTON, TX.  FIRE DEPARTMENT ASSUMED IT WAS FROM A RAIL CAR OF ANHYDROUS HYDROGEN FLUORIDE IN THE FAUNA SIDING AND CLOSED HIGHWAY 90 WHICH PARALLELS THE SIDING.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ALSO RECOMMENDED SHELTER IN PLACE FOR RESIDENTS IN A ONE MILE RADIUS OF THE SIDING.  RESPONDED AND INSPECTED CARS IN THE SIDING AND FOUND ALL CARS SECURE AND NO ODOR. HIGHWAY 90 WAS REOPENED AND THE SHELTER IN PLACE LIFTED WITHIN 90 MINUTES.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Over-pressurized
column168: ON ABOVE TIME AND DATE, MGR. CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DENNIS M JOHNSON WAS NOTIFIED OF THIS CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHEN THE CAR WAS BEING MOVED.  INVESTIGATION BY MR JOHNSON REVEALED THAT THE MANWAY BOLTS SECURING THE MANWAY WERE ALL LESS THAN HAND TIGHT WHICH CAUSED THE LEAK. THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE SECURED PROPERLY, AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION SHOWED THAT THIS CAR WAS AN IMPORT FROM MEXICO AND THE MANWAY MIGHT HAVE OPENED FOR INSPECTION AND NOT RESECURED PROPERLY.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND AGREED TO PAY ALL CHARGES FOR CONTRACTOR TO RESECURE THE CAR.  NO PRODUCT TOUCHED THE GROUND.

ON JUNE 3, 2001 AT 2100 HOURS SR. SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, DAVID SACHS RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE SPARKS YARDMASTER REPORTING A TANKCAR LEAKING IN THE AREA OF PATRICK NV.  SACHS RESPONDED TO THE AREA AND CHECKED ALL THE TANK CARS IN THE SIDING.  HE FOUND  ACFX 89049 ON THE SEIRRA PACIFIC SIDING AT WUNOTOO M.P. 260.75 ON THE NEVADA SUBDIVISION LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM VALVE. IT APPEARED THAT SOMEONE INTENTIONALLY REMOVED THE VALVE CAP AND OPENED THE VALVE RELEASING THE PRODUCT.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 2500 GALLONS OF FUEL OIL RELEASED.  THE INCIDENT IS BEING INVESTIGATED AS A VANDALISM.

column168: LIQUID MATERIAL WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM TRAILER #7-1937.  SHIPPING DOCUMENTS WERE REVIEWED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER WAS A CORROSIVE LIQUID (ETHANOLAMINE) CFWY NOTIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC.  A RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO THE TERMINAL.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE LOAD WAS NOT PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED AND THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED CAUSING SOME OF THE FIVE GALLON CONTAINERS TO BE CRUSHED.  THE RELEASE HAD IMPACTED A SMALL AREA OF THE GRAVEL PARKING AREA.  THERE WERE 6 CONTAINERS THAT WERE BREACHED AND 8 OTHER CONTAINERS THAT WERE NOT LEAKING BUT NOT IN SHIPPABLE CONDITION.  20 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE 6 BREACHED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED IN A POLY OVERPACK DRUM.  THE OTHER 8 CONTAINERS WERE PLACED IN ANOTHER OVERPACK DRUM.  SPILL CLEANUP MATERIAL (ABSORBENTS, BROOMS, PPE) WERE PLACED IN ANOTHER DRUM (3 DRUMS WERE GENERATED).  THE DRUMS WERE PLACED IN STORAGE PENDING DISPOSAL.  E.M.I. ISSUED THIS INCIDENT A JOB NUMBER (11277)

CFWY EMPLOYEE WAS WALKING BY CYLINDER AND HEARD IT LEAKING.  ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED.  E.M.I. DISPATCHED A RESPONSE TEAM.  (MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL) TO THE SITE.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE CYLINDER WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM WELDSEAM.  THERE WERE ALSO SOME SCRATCH MARKS INDICATING IT HAD BEEN POSSIBLY STRUCK BY THE FORKS OF A FORKLIFT.  THE RESPONSE TEAM PLUGGED THE LEAK AND PUT A STRAP AROUND IT TO SECURE THE PATCH.  C.S. HALON & EQUIPMENT SALES (SHIPPER) WAS CONTACTED.  THEY DISPATCHED PERSONNEL TO THE SITE AND TRANSPORTED THE CYLINDER BACK TO THEIR FACILITY SO THAT THEY COULD TRANSFER THE PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED CYLINDER TO A GOOD CYLINDER.  (E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 11234

THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED AND THREE ONE-GALLON CANS OF TOUCHDOWN CONTACT CEMENT WERE DISCOVERED INSIDE. THE TOP OF ONE OF THE CANS HAD COME OFF AND THE CONTENTS HAD COMPLETELY LEAKED OUT. FOUR BAGS HAD BECOME CONTAMINATED WITH THE LEAKING MATERIAL AND THE AIRCRAFT BIN FLOOR WAS ALSO CONTAMINATED (2'X4 AREA). AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED TO RESPOND. BY THE TIME THEY ARRIVED THE CONTACT CEMENT HAD SOLIDIFIED. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND INFORMATION REGARDING THE CUSTOMER AND THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS FORWARDED FOR THEIR INVESTIGATION.

column168: ON JUNE 14,2001 JCI DRIVER BART MADANS WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TO N.Y. WATER SERVICE IN SEAFORD, NY THE DELIVERY CALLED FOR FIVE STOPS, WHILE MAKING THE FOURTH STOP BART HEARD AIR COMING FROM THE LINE THAT IS CONNECTED TO THE RUPTURE DISC. HE THEN PROCEEDED TO START SHUTTING DOWN ALL OF HIS VALVES, HOWEVER BEFORE HE COULD FINISH THE RUPTURE DISC HAD BLOWN SPRAYING APPROX.10 GALLONS OF BLEACH INTO A CONTAINMENT AREA. WHEN MAKING THE DELIVERY BART WAS ON AN INCLINE WITH THE REAR OF THE TRAILER IN THE DOWN HILL POSITION HE MOVED THE TRAILER TO LEVEL GROUND AND THE LEAK FROM THE HOSE HAD STOPPED. THE MAINTENANCE MAN FROM N.Y. WATER WAS THERE WHEN THIS HAPPENED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL IMMEDIATELY. BART THEN REPAIRED THE RUPTURE DISC AND CONTINUED ON WITH THE REST OF THE DELIVERY WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. NO ONE WAS SPRAYED WITH THE BLEACH AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES.
