LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER-CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC OF A LEAKING TANK CAR, GATX 74946, A LOAD OF MALEIC ANHYDRIDE AT THE 18TH STREET YARD.  THE CAR FOREMAN ALSO ADVISED HIM THAT PERSONNEL WERE BEING EVACUATED DUE TO SEVERE EYE IRRITATION AND CORROSIVE FUMES.  AS A PRECAUTION, TRANSPORTATION ARTERIES IN THE AREA OF THE YARD WERE ALSO CLOSED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  AS MR. SEKAVEC WOULD BE RESPONDING FROM DES MOINES, CHRISTI HORNICK, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS WAS NOTIFIED TO INITIATE A RESPONSE FOR THE RAILROAD.  HAZ-MAT RESPONSE, EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, WAS ALSO NOTIFIED TO RESPOND.  ON HER ARRIVAL, MRS. HORNICK FUNCTIONED AS A LIASON/RESOURCE PERSON FOR RESPONDING PERSONNEL.  SHE FACILITATED  CONTACT BETWEEN THE VARIOUS GROUPS ON SCENE SUCH AS CLAIMS, OPERATING AND ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS FOR THE RAILROAD AS WELL AS THE SHIPPER AND KCK FIRE DEPARTMENT.  INITIAL EVALUATION OF THE TANK CAR REVEALED A POSSIBLE STAIN ON ONE SIDE OF THE CAR.  MR. SEKAVEC ARRIVED ON SCENE AND CONFERRED WITH ALL PARTIES INVOLVED.  PERSONNEL ADVISED THAT THE ODOR WAS A FISHY OR AMMONIA-TYPE ODOR.  THIS SPECIFIC TANK CAR WAS BEING INVESTIGATED DUE TO ITS LOCATION IN THE YARD.  RAILROAD PERSONNEL WERE IN THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY OF THIS CAR WHEN THEY BEGAN COMPLAINING OF IRRITATION TO THEIR EYES AND RESPIRATORY TRACT. INVESTIGATION OF CARS IN THE YARD REVEALED THIS TO BE ONE OF ONLY TWO CARS IN THIS AREA OF THE YARD CARRYING ANY PLACARDED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE OTHER CAR WAS ANOTHER CAR OF MALEIC ANHYDRIDE ADJACENT TO GATX 74946.  MR. SEKAVEC ACCOMPANIED HAZ-MAT RESPONSE PERSONNEL INTO THE AREA OF THE TANK CAR AND REVIEWED THE EVENTS THAT HAD TAKEN PLACE.  HAZ-MAT RESPONSE PERSONNEL REMOVED THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE FROM THE CAR, VERIFIED THAT THERE WAS NO DEFECT WITH THE VALVE AND REPLACED THE VALVE.  AIR MONITORING BY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZ-MAT RESPONSE PERSONNEL INDICATED NO DETECTABLE RELEASE OF MATERIAL FROM THE CAR IN QUESTION.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND ALL AFFECTED TRANSPORTATION ARTERIES WERE REOPENED. SUBSEQUENT CALLS ON JUNE 12 FROM BOTH THE ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY AND KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT INDICATED THAT PROCTOR AND GAMBLE HAD EXPERIENCED A RELEASE OF DIMETHYLAMINE FORM THEIR PLANT JUST SOUTH OF THE 18TH STREET YARD ON THE EVENING OF THE 11TH BEGINNING AT APPROXIMATELY THE SAME TIME AS THE ODOR WAS REPORTED TO RMCC.  THERE WAS NO RELEASE FROM THE TANK CAR.  THIS REPORT IS BEING FILED IN ORDER TO COMPLY WITH CFR 171.16 (A).

THE RUPTURE DISK WAS REPLACED AND THE TANK CAR AND TRAIN WERE RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

AS A RESULT THE PRODUCT INSIDE THE CAR HAD ENOUGH FORCE TO RELEASE THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. AND DISCHARGE APPROX. 1/4 POUND OF PHOSPHORUS. WHEN THE PRODUCT CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE AIR IT IGNITED AND BURNED OFF IMMEDIATELY. AFTER BURNING THERE WERE SOME FUMES AND THE WIND WAS OUT OF THE SOUTHWEST. UNION PACIFIC FRUIT EXPRESS EMPLOYEES WERE ASKED TO MOVE WEST IN ORDER TO AVOID THE FUMES. THE CAR WAS PLACED IN BAD ORDER STATUS AND PLACED ON HOLD. ON 06/26 GARY PETERSON FROM MONSANTO ARRIVED AND INSPECTED THE CAR. THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS IN OPERATING ORDER BUT THE NITROGEN BLANKET HAD BEEN RELEASED. UNION PACIFIC PURCHASED NITROGEN AND REGULATOR AND INSTALLED A NEW NITROGEN BLANKET OF 12PSI IN THE TANK CAR. THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED ON 6/26 TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER, DOW CHEMICAL WERE ALSO NOTIFIED. MTO KEITH NORRIS ADVISED THERE WAS NO PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE CAR. HOWEVER, THERE WERE WET MARKS ON THE SIDE OF THE TANK CAR FROM APPARRENT SLOSHING DURING CAR MOVEMENT. THE CAR WS SPOTTED AT RIP TRACK 503, BIG SPRING YARD AND SECURED FOR THE NIGHT. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE DENNIS WOOSTER ADVISED MGR MCNUTT THAT A RESPONSE TEAM WOULD BE DISPATCHED BY DOW CHEMICAL ON THE MORNING  OF 06/23/2001. MGR MCNUTT WAS LATER NOTIFIED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING AND THAT A 4FT X 6FT AREA OF GROUND ON TRACK #4 WAS SATURATED WITH PRODUCT. ALSO, ONE UPRR EMPLOYEE REPORTED A HEADACHE DUE TO A STRONG ODOR IN THE AREA. MTO NORRIS AND MGR MCNUTT RESPONDED. MGR MCNUTT REQUESTED RMCC NOTIFY EAGLE (UPRR CONTRACTOR) TO RESPOND AND NEUTRALIZE THE ACID SPILL MR TIM SCOTT, DOW CHEMICAL RESPONSE MANAGER REQUESTED ASSISTANCE WITH DAMAGE ASSESSMENT OF LEAKING TANK CAR. TANK CAR INSPECTION WAS COMPLETED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID LINE FLANGE HAD LEAKED ACID AND CORRODED THE BOLTS. EAGLE RESPONSE PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND REMOVED THE LIQUID LINE BONNET AND INSTALLED A NEW BLIND FLANGE GASKET AND REPLACED THE CORRODED BOLTS. EAGLE PERSONNEL SECURED TANK CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION ONTO CONSIGNEE. EAGLE RESPONSE PERSONNEL ALSO NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL AREA.

TANK CAR COCX 288085 WAS PART OF A CUT OF CARS BEING SHOVED AT THE UNION PACIFIC RAIL YARD AT WESTWEGO, LA. AT ABOUT 2100 HOURS THIS CAR AND SEVERAL OTHER EMPTY CARS DERAILED, LEAVING COCX 288085 ON ITS SIDE. SHORTLY THEREAFTER THE VERY VISCOUS LIQUID CONTENTS BEGAN SLOWLY LEAKING OUT OF THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE INCLUDING THE WESTWEGO FIRE & POLICE DEPTS., JEFFERSON PARISH HAZMAT, LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENV. QUALITY , CHEMTREC, KEIL CHEMICAL, THE SHIPPER, CHEVRON, THE CONSIGNEE, UPRR MANAGER OF ENV. FIELD OPERATIONS, T.M. ROBINSON, EAGLE CONST. & ENV SERVICES AND HULCHER PROFESSIONAL SERVICES. THE WESTWEGO FIRE AND POLICE DEPTS. BLOCKED OFF LOUISIANA STREET FOR THEIR EQUIPMENT, BUT DUE TO THE REMOTE LOCATION OF THE DERAILMENT IN THE YARD THERE WAS NO OFF SITE IMPACT.UPON ARRIVAL ROBINSON HAD TECHNICIANS FROM EAGLE PLACE A 55 GALLON DRUM UNDER THE LEAKING VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. THIS COMPLETELY CONTAINED THE LEAKAGE UNTIL HULCHER RERAILED THE CAR AT WHICH TIME THE LEAK STOPPED. IN ADDITION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE VALVE WAS LEAKING AT A RATE OF 3.3 GALLONS PER HOUR. AN ESTIMATED 14 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED ON THE SOIL. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS RECOVERED BY EAGLE AND WILL BE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF AT A LATER TIME. AN ESTIMATED 29 GALLONS PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED IN THE 55 GALLON DRUM. THIS MATERIAL WILL BE FORWARDED ON TO CHEVRON. AFTER THE TANK CAR WAS RERAILED THE CONTENTS WERE TRANSFERED INTO CARGO TANK TRUCKS AND FORWARDED ONTO CHEVRON AT OAK POINT, LA

ON JUNE 20,2001, LANE. SEKAVEC, MANGER-CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED OF A GONDOLA CNW 350321, THAT WAS ENTRAINED IN  A CUT FOR THE IMRL AT NEFF YARD THAT WAS LEAKING WATER FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE GONDOLA. THE CAR WAS PLACARDED NA 3077, HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID, NICKEL/PRECIOUS METAL CONCENTRATE, F006. INVESTIGATION OF THE CAR REVEALED THAT THE TARP COVERING THE LOAD HAD COLLECTED AND EXCESSIVE AMOUNT OF RAINWATER AND ONE OF THE LAP SEAMS HAD RIPPED, ALLOWING THE RAINWATER TO PERMEATE THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR. THIS WATER, IN TURN , RAN OUT WEEP HOLES AND OTHER PENETRATIONS AT THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR. THE LEACHATE COLLECTED IN A STANDING POOL OF RAINWATER BETWEEN TRACKS 303 AND 304 IN THE OUTBOUND YARD AT NEFF. PREPARATIONS WERE MADE FOR AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR (ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALISTS INC.) TO RESPOND TO VACUUM UP THE CONTAMINATED RAINWATER AND DISPOSE OF IT PROPERLY. EQUIPMENT WAS PUT IN PLACE AND OPERATIONS WERE STARTED VACUUMING THE WATER. AT APPROXIMATELY 2345, AN INTENSE THUNDERSTORM MOVED THROUGH THE AREA, MAKING IT EXTREMELY DIFFICULT TO CONTINUE VACUUM OPERATIONS.MR. SEKAVEC CONFERRED WITH CHRISTI HORNICK, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS AS TO ANY OTHER SOLUTIONS THAT MAY BE VIABLE, WITH NONE BEING FOUND. IT WAS DECIDED TO SUSPEND VACUUM OPERATIONS UNTIL THE RAIN STOPPED AND CONDITIONS WERE MORE FAVORABLE. AT THIS POINT, APPROXIMATELY 6,000 GALLONS OF CONTAMINATED WATER HAD BEEN VACUUMED UP.MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCE OFFICIALS WERE NOTIFIED THAT OPERATIONS WERE BEING STOPPED. EFFORTS WERE THEN CONCENTRATED ON INSTALLING TEMPORARY DAMS AT THE EAST AND WEST ENDS OF THE ORIGINAL SPILL AREA IN AN ATTEMPT TO CONTAIN AS MUCH OF THE ORIGINAL CONTAMINATED WATER AS POSSIBLE. PERSONNEL WERE ALSO USED TO INSTALL A TEMPORARY COVER ON THE AFFECTED GONDOLA TO PREVENT ANY MORE RAIN FROM ENTERING AND SATURATING THE LOAD. FINALLY, TEMPORARY CONTAINMENT BASINS WERE BUILT AROUND EACH CORNER OF THE GONDOLA TO CAPTURE AS MUCH OF THE CONTAMINATION AS POSSIBLE. THE FOLLOWING DAY, THE TEMPORARY CONTAINMENT BASINS WERE VACUUMED CLEAR. WATER SAMPLES WERE TAKEN AT THE POINT OF INITIAL RELEASE AS WELL AS AT THE OUTFALL OFF OF RAILROAD PROPERTY. PREPARATIONS WERE MADE TO THE LOAD IN THE CAR TO APPLY PATCHES TO PREVENT ANY MORE ESCAPE OF PRODUCT OR CONTAMINATED WATER. AFTER THESE PATCHES WERE IN PLACE AND ALL OTHER HOLES WERE SEALED, A NEW TARP WAS INSTALLED ON THE CAR AND THE CAR RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION. THE CONTAINMENT BASINS WERE DISMANTLED AND PLACED IN DRUMS FOR LATER DISPOSAL, AS WAS ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL FROM THE CONTAINMENT AND PATCHING EFFORTS.

23. D. - FROM A TRANSPORTATION COST DECONTAMINATED/CLEAN UP SHOULD BE $43,000.00.  BECAUSE OF AN UNUSUAL FINDING IN THE REMEDIATION PHASE, THE COST OF CLEANUP HAS INCREASED ABOVE $50,000.  SITE DESCRIPTION- ON  JUNE 15, 2001 AT APPROXIMATELY 10:20 A.M. A CIP/OXY PRIVATE FLEET DRIVER WAS DELIVERING A ^3500 GALLON T/T LOAD OF 50% SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION TO GRIFFIN LLC LOCATED AT 12701 ALMEDA RD., HOUSTON, TX.  THE DRIVER, MR. CLIFTON FOREMAN (EMPLOYED BY TRANSPORT DRIVERS, INC.), WAS MAKING HIS SECOND DELIVERY OF THE MORNING.  THE WEATHER WAS PARTLY CLOUDY, 93 F, WIND SE @ 20 MPH.  THE UNLOADING TANKS AND PRODUCT LINES AT GRIFFIN ARE LOCATED BEHIND THE MAIN WAREHOUSE ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE BUILDING.  THE TRANSFER AREA HAS A PARTIAL CONCRETE PAD AND IS ENCLOSED ON 3 SIDES BY CONCRETE RETAINING WALLS SURROUNDING PRODUCT STORAGE TANKS.  THE TRANSFER AREA HAS A SAFETY SHOWER AND HAS BEEN RECENTLY EQUIPPED WITH A SMALL AIR OPERATED SUMP PUMP TO REMOVE STORMWATER FROM THE CONCRETE PAD.  PRIOR ACTIONS TAKEN AND DEVIATIONS.  THE DRIVER PULLED INTO THE AREA AND BACKED THE TRAILER INTO THE UNLOADING AREA.  NO GRIFFIN OPERATIONS PERSONNEL WERE IN ATTENDANCE OR ASSISTED IN TRANSFER PREPARATION PROCEDURES.  UPON DISEMBARKING FROM THE TRACTOR MR. FOREMAN PUT ON SOME OF HIS PPE TO DO THE TRANSFER AND PROCEEDED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE TRANSFER HOSE OWNED BY GRIFFIN FOR THE PRODUCT TRANSFER IS APPROXIMATELY 3 FEET LONG AND PERMANENTLY CONNECTED TO THE PRODUCT PIPING.  SOP CALLED FOR THE DRIVER TO BACK THE TRAILER SUFFICIENTLY FAR ENOUGH INTO THE AREA TO ATTACH THE PRODUCT HOSE.  IN DO SO, THE DRIVER ENTERED AN AREA WITH LITTLE ROOM FOR MOVING AROUND PIPING. THE DRIVER HAD DIFFICULTY OBTAINING PROPER CAMLOCK FITTING ALIGNMENT BECAUSE THE HOSE LENGTH WAS INSUFFICIENT.  SOP ALSO STATED THE DRIVER WAS TO ATTACH THE HOSE TO THE TRAILER OUTLET FITTING, OPEN THE TOP AIR VALVE, CONNECT PLANT AIR SUPPLY HOSE TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER, AND PRESSURIZE THE TRAILER TO APPROX. 25 PSIG.  THE DRIVER, BY HIS OWN ACCOUNT, DEVIATED FROM SOP DURING ATTACHMENT OF THE HOSE BECAUSE THE SUMP PUMP RAN DRY DISTRACTING HIM.  THE DRIVER STATED HE STOPPED FROM CONNECTING THE PRODUCT HOSE TO SHUT THE PUMP DOWN TO PREVENT DAMAGE.  MR. FOREMAN STATED HE DOES NOT REMEMBER BEING COMPLETELY SURE THAT THE HOSE CAMLOCK FITTINGS WERE COMPLETELY STRAIGHT AND CLAMPED IN PLACE.  THE HOSE CLAMPS WERE NOT SECURED.  ACCIDENT SUMMARY.  THE DRIVER STATED HE PARTIALLY OPENED THE EXTERNAL VALVE BECAUSE IT IS SOMETIMES DIFFICULT TO OPERATE WITH PRODUCT PRESSURE APPLIED.  THE DRIVER THEN OPENED THE INTERNAL HYDRAULIC VALVE. THE CAMLOCK FITTING ON THE HOSE CAME LOOSE FROM THE TRAILER FITTING ALMOST INSTANTLY AND STRUCK MR. FOREMAN IN THE CHEST AREA KNOCKING HIM BACKWARD OVER THE RETAINING WALL TO HIS NORTH.  AS HE FELL, HIS HARD HAT, CHEMICAL GOGGLES AND SPLASH SHIELD FELL FROM HIS HEAD AND PRODUCT SPRAYED ONTO HIS FACE.  FORTUNATELY, MR. FOREMAN KEPT HIS EYES AND MOUTH CLOSED PREVENTING MORE SERIOUS

column168: FILE: 2140 F & D, SHIPPER: TNT 8KYPAK, AWB #LIQ 16124800016 RDG. ON 6/23/2001 AT 0108 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED ON AIRCRAFT N848AX, BELLY 4, PARKED AT GATE B-14 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177. PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS JEFFREY KIDDER AND CHRISTI KIRKER, AS WELL AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR TAMARA RAMIREZ, DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL WE FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGING. WE REMOVED THIS FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND BEGAN OUR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THIS BOX WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN 3 X 1 METAL CANS WITH METAL FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES. EACH CLOSURE HAD TAPE ON IT AND EACH CAN WAS WRAPPED IN BUBBLE WRAP, NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED. THE CONTENTS OF THESE CANS ARE AS FOLLOWS: 1 X 1L - CITRUS FRESH MOD LX104268 - FLAMMABLE -LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 0.5 OUNCES FROM LOOSE CLOSURE. THE PRODUCT CAUSED THE TAPE TO FAIL. 1 X 1 L - OCEAN FRESH LX71649 - NOT REGULATED. 1 X 1L - FRESH FLORAL MOD LX102720 - NOT REGULATED. WE REPLACED THESE ITEMS INTO THE BOX, RESEALED IT, AND PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. WE PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND PLACED THE RECOVERY DRUM INTO THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL. THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS WELL VENTILATED AND THE BELLY FLOOR WAS CLEANED WITH SOAP AND WATER, BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED. THERE WERE TWO EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR. THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREA. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES WERE REPORTED IN THESE EMPLOYEES. NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED. THEY WERE GIVEN A COPY OF THE MSDS AND A COPY OF THE MSDS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT. CLEAR OF SCENE 0161.

THE DELIVER DRIVER NOTICED IT BECAUSE OF THE SMELL.  HE BROUGHT IT TO MY ATTENTION AND I IMMEDIATELY PLACED IT IN OUR HAZ AREA.  ILN SENT A SALVAGE DRUM TO PLACE IT IN AND IT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THERE WAS NO PERSON OR PROPERTY DAMAGED. PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS LORINE HARNER, THOMAS CASPER, AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR MICHAEL FRYE DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER. INSPECTION NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOORS. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED AND SECURED FOR INSPECTION. WHILE INSPECTING THE CONTENTS, NOTED THE DRUMS AT THE LADING TO BE THE HAZARDOUS COMMODITY, SECURED BY 4X4 INCH WEDGES NAILED TO THE FLOOR. TWO ADDITIONAL DRUMS OF PRODUCT WERE ON THE TOP TIER, SECURED BY A SINGLE 2X4 PLACED INTO THE CORRUGATED SIDE WALL. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED METHOD, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED PROTOCOL FOR THE SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES TRANSPORTED BY RAIL PER THE AAR BOE PAMPHLET 6C. ONE DRUM WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP. IT APPEARS THE DRUM ABRADED THE SIDE WALL DURING TRANSIT, CAUSING A 1 INCH CRACK IN THE ROLLING HOOP, RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 34 GALLONS DURING TRANSIT. THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK FOR SECUREMENT. THE REMAINING FREIGHT WAS REMOVED AND DECONED. THE FLOORING WAS REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF, ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED DRUM. THE LADING WAS PLACED BACK INTO A REPLACEMENT CONTAINER, HJCU 852047, AND PROPERTY SECURED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RMCC.

15:45 HMONE RECEIVED A CALL FROM JOE REEDER, FLEMING AND HALL. HE ADVISED HE GOT  A CALL FROM COVENANT AND THEY HAVE A SPILL NEAR BLYTHE, CA. THEY HAVE PHOSPHORIC ACID LEAKING OUT OF A TRAILER(#34345). HE ADVISE THE COVENANT DRIVER (ARTHUR BOSTICK) WAS CONTACTED BY ANOTHER DRIVER IN REFERENCE TO THE LEAK BECAUSE THE PRODUCT WAS GETTING ON THE 2ND DRIVERS TRACTOR. BOTH TRACTORS ARE ON THE SHOULDER. THEY NEED A TEAM TO RESPOND AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL. HMONE ADVISED A TEAM WOULD BE CALLED TO RESPOND AND HMONE WOULD CALL BACK WITH AN ETA. 15:47  HMONE CALLED ZACHARY DITMAR, COVENANT, TO GET MORE DETAILS. 15:50 HMONE CALLED MP ENVIRONMENTAL TO SEE HOW FAR OUT THEY WERE. SPOKE WITH LARRY CHASE. HE ADVISED THEY WERE A GOOD 3 HOURS AWAY.  16:00 HMONE CALLED THE OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES TO REPORT THE SPILL. THE CONTROL # IS 013474.  16:05 HMONE CALLED ARTHUR BOSTICK. HE PASSED HIS PHONE TO ALAN COOK, CALTRANS. HE ADVISED THE RIVERSIDE COUNTY HAZ-MAT TEAM WAS ONSITE AND PREPARING TO ENTER THE TRAILER. HE BELIEVED A DRUM FELL OVER AND WAS PUNCTURED CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE TRAILER. HE BELIEVES BETWEEN 30-50 GALLONS HAS BEEN RELEASED. THE PRODUCT IS ON THE ROADWAY, THE SHOULDER, COVENANT TRAILER AND THE 2ND TRANSPORTERS TRACTOR. HE ADVISED THE (2) WEST BOUND LANES HAEVEBEEN DIVERTED. CALTRANS HAS  CALLED CONSOLIDATED WASTE INDUSTRIES, INC. TO RESPOND. HMONE ADVISED CWI WAS UNDER CONTRACT WITH HMONE AND THAT WOULD BE OK.

DURING UNLOADING THE DRIVER AND THE CONSIGNEE FOUND THREE PAILS OF H/M THAT HAD BEEN DAMAGED AND WERE LEAKING. THEY APPEAR TO HAVE BEEN RAMMED WITH A FORK LIFT. ONE PAIL HAD A FORK HOLE AND THE OTHER TWO HAD BEEN CRUSHED. THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT. THEY GAVE THE DRIVER MATERIALS TO CLEAN UP THE TRAILER FLOOR.
